column14: I really wanted to love these shoes. I was hoping for an attractive and functional shoe. I wanted them to be my cute, go to, wear all summer shoes but sadly they're not. They are super cute. And they're very well made. But for all day wear they are just not comfortable enough. Not for me anyway. I work on my feet. I'm standing and walking on concrete floors for 4-5 hours at a stretch. When wearing these shoes my feet begin to hurt after about 3 hours. They fit well (though I have suffered through a few painful heel blisters breaking them in) and they are comfortable in that they are not tight and they do not pinch but they offer very little arch support and the soles are not made to stand up to hours of concrete floor usage. I'll probably stick to wearing them on my days off when I know that I won't be doing a lot of standing or walking. Luckily I got them on sale for about $70.00 so I don't feel too let down!

column6: evolv Men's Cruzer Approach Shoe
column13: well designed, unique features, very comfortable
column14: Extremely comfortable and look even better than I expected.  The inner material is very soft, very smooth and has no sharp inner seams.  The removable insole is thoroughly padded and looks as if it will be easily washable.  The sole rubber is super tacky and grips well.  "Slipper mode" with the heel stomped in is pretty convenient, however MY FAVORITE FEATURE is the split tongue, I had never seen this before this model shoe and Im now convinced that all shoes should be made this way.  There are two tongues on this shoe that overlap in the center with each one being sewn to one side under the eyelets.  This is cool because its like how a work boot has a connected 1-piece tounge to keep out dirt, which this does, but it also accommodates my particularly wide foot.  I bought these in the same size I wear in classic vans.  These shoes have a basic streamlined profile but more support and comfort than other canvas shoes I've had in the past.  I highly recommend, I'm buying a pair for my girlfriend too

column6: Vionic Women's Tide Sequins Sandals
column14:
These shoes fit me like a glove and support my arch so well. They are definitely the most comfortable pair of shoes that I own. I am sure I will be buying many pairs of orthaheel shoes in the future. As for sizing. For me at least, it is the same fit as a dress shoe would be. I am a size 6 in dress shoes and a size 6 in these fits me perfectly. Sometimes when buying flip flops, a size 6 is a bit too small, but not with these.

They are nice looking shoes, too, but Im really all about the comfort, as I have had chronic plantar fasciitis for 15 years, have fibromyalgia, and have the world's most sensitive feet. I rarely find shoes that are comfortable enough on my feet to wear, so these shoes have made me very happy.

column6: Nunn Bush Men's Randall Gladiator Sandal
column14:
I'm a huge Nunn Bush fan. I have many dress shoes from them.

I purchased size 10 and size 11 because I was unsure the fit when ordering it from Amazon.com I liked the sandals when I first put them on. I really did. But I've worn them once for a couple hours and the memory foam never went back to the way it was supposed to. It's now a permanent indent from my feet. I thought memory foam was able to bounce-back to its original shape (hence the "memory" designation). But unlike a memory foam mattress or mattress cover these just created permanent indents. I'm not sure if I'm going to keep them based on this design. Wish I had known this information prior to purchase.

I also wished I had seen the disclaimer information regarding shipping. I had no idea at time of purchase that shipping costs would be incurred for sending the wrong size back. It was an oversight on my part but it was a huge let down to have to pay $12 ground shipping back because I wanted to check the size. Had I known this I would have went to an outlet or store and tried them on first. Now I know. I most likely won't order any Nunn Bush products online anymore. Nothing against the company, it's just a lot of money to pay to return something that is brand new and you lose about 1/4 of the money for really nothing.

column6: KEEN Women's Rose Sandal
column13: Not a great sandal for excessive walking - failed the Disney test.
column14:
I was so ready to love these sandals. I bought them for a 5 day Disney trip with my two kids. I was also 5 months pregnant at the time of the trip (June). First, what the others say about the strap across the top of your foot is true, within a couple of hours it was way too tight and causing a lot of friction on my foot. I had to basically make the Velcro part on top super loose so that it was only the sewn on elastic part that was holding on the sandal.
Second, my heels had awful blisters by the end of day 2. The friction from my heel rubbing against the back of the sandal was awful and my arches were killing me. Overall not a great experience but when worn for short periods of time they can be comfortable. I just would not recommend for any activity where there is a lot of walking. My 3 year old wears Keen sandals and loves them but for me, I might try a different style next time around. These are sitting in my closet and haven't made much of an appearance since June. Disappointing for the money I paid for them.

column6: ECCO Women's Touch 25 Stride Dress Sandal
column13: They are great - so great I am purchasing the other color ...
column14: Adjustable slides are tough to find, so I  was excited to see these shoes.  I first saw this style at an ecco outlet store and had to try them on. I bought a pair at the outlet store and have come to Amazon to purchase the other color also. They are great ,  The style is sleek and understated and because of this they can dress up or down.  The footbed is soft and comfortable and even has a bit of arch support.  I have mentioned the the adjustable straps, which are great.  As I typically wear a wide width shoe, I was interested in the comments that the shoe is narrow.  For me, the adjustability of the straps compensates for the for the width and, the straps do not dig in at all. About sizing on ecco shoes.  I have always worn a size 38 in ecco dress shoes vs a 37 in their sporty sandals.  I decided to compare the two directly.  It seems that the 38 in this style is almost the same as the size 37 "Jab" sandals (which fit fine). Interestingly enough, the 37 "Offroad Lite" sandals as about 1/2-1 inch wider and longer all around although sold as a size smaller! The photo shows the difference in sizes.  Listed left to right.  ecco Vibration flat - size 38, so is: ecco Touch 25 Slide - size 38, appears quite small. ecco Offroad Lite - size 37 ecco Jab sandal - size 37   I always size down in ecco casual sandals (37/6); dressier ones choose my actual size (38/7).  Hope this is helpful.

I ordered these sandals from Amazon back in May, in Dark Earth, and they were exactly as pictured in the photo. Loved them enough to want a backup pair for when mine wear out, so I reordered in July. The sandals that arrived looked much like the originals, except that the material was suede, rather than nubuck, and the color was much darker brown. I looked on Merrell's website and at other online retailers, and can't find any evidence that Merrell ever made this shoe in suede (not to mention that very dark brown), so I'm puzzled and annoyed. The only place I see images that match the shoes Amazon sent me is on eBay. (You can Google it to see the difference.)

In any case, I very much like the nubuck pair that I bought in May. Comfortable, versatile, sturdy. A bit narrow, but that matters little because of the design. The shoe itself is great for me - I'm docking a star because I didn't get the real deal the second time around, and now I have the hassle of a return. It's a good thing Amazon makes it easy; otherwise, I'd be complaining more loudly.

column6: Gusti Leder nature \Harley\" Genuine Leather Holdall Petite Handbag Vintage Unisex Brown R25b"
column13: MORE STUNNING THAN IN THE PICTURES!!!...
column14:
This is my third Gusti bag that I've purchased, with each purchase I get more and more impressed with these bags/purses/duffles, whatever you chose to call them. I am usually an avid Coach "junkie", owning almost an entire line of products, I can honestly say that Gusti is a top contender of my choice of purses to carry other than Coach.

I've read several reviews all referring to the "smell". Let me say, THESE ARE GENUINE LEATHER PRODUCTS, THERE IS GOING TO BE A "SMELL" TO THEM...the "smell" every has negatively reviewed does dissappate over time and with use. I will caution those that have not purchased this particular line of geniune leather goods, or truly genuine leather products, yes, the "smell" can be overwhelming, but as I said, it does slowly subsides over time and use. Nearly every leather product that I have owned and do own has a "smell", it's natural, it's always going to be there, and if you have an aversion to the "smell" of genuine leather, this may not be a product you'd want to purchase. Leather is the skin or hide of an animal, usually a cow, but can be goat, sheep, lamb, buffalo, deer, elk, moose, shall I keep going? The skin or hide is treated or "tanned", during this process, as with any flesh, there is going to be a "smell". Every skin or hide, depending on the animal produces its' own unique "smell". It's a "smell" you either like, or dislike. Me, I personally like the "smell" of leathers, it's a natural product, a natural "smell". All I carry are leather purses, I only wear leather shoes, my winter coats are leather, some are leather and fur. It's a matter of personal choice, personal perference, and to be honest, in my own opinion, leather products last longer, are more durable, are well worth the price, and to me, nothing beats the "smell" of a genuine leather product.

This bag, like the small round Gusti that's offered at the same price, are more on the lines of a purse, carry-all, camera bag, etc...this bag isn't what I would refer to as a weekender or even an overnight bag, it's small, the dimisions are clearly stated in the description area of the advertisement, so if you're looking for a larger duffle or larger piece of luggage, you'll probably have to look through the Gusti line of products, carefully read over the dimisions, I'd even go as far as to suggest, use a measuring tape so you'll know "exactly" how big this or any other item is so there is no surprise or disappointment regarding how small or how big this bag is.

The color of the bag I received is the color of a smooth decanter of scotch. It is "distressed", meaning there are natural flaws in the leather, which again, in my own opinion, gives this bag character. The color will usually darken over time and with use, that is a natural process of leather. If you're expecting a perfectly dyed product, without natural flaws and mars, this isn't probably going to be a bag you'll want to purchase. I will be including pictures to show the color, the size, and the beautiful qualities this bag offers.

This bag offers three compartments, two smaller ones and a larger one. The largest compartment is the center compartment, with each of the smaller compartment on either side. Each compartment offers dual zippers that interlock, interlocking zippers often offer the use of luggage locks, which can give an added piece of security (luggage locks are not included with this bag but can be purchased separately). The crossbody strap is wider than most crossbody straps, the straps are undetachable. The front pocket has a nice securing buckle, the buckle is metal, not cheap plastic knock offs. The quality of construction is fantastic. All seams are sewn, not glued and made to look sewn, they are actually sewn together. Very nice, durable, and quality construction.

Overall, regardless of the negative reviews that I've read, I'm offering a review that isn't negative, that tries to provide an overview of the quality of this bag, a brief explanation of the "smell" that surrounds this bag, and pictures to give the potential purchasers of this bag a better idea of the size, shape, and color. A bonus that is included (at least it was included in my shipment) is a small tin of leather treatment salve and a storage bag for the bag when not in use. Shipment was right on time, it was delivered on a Sunday, by USPS, which was guaranteed by Amazon Prime when I ordered this bag. In my own honest opinion, this bag is more stunning in person than what is shown in the pictures, and with each Gusti piece I purchase in the future, I know that I am purchasing an excellent, durable, beautifully constructed, quality bag. I would recommend this bag to anyone that asks if this bag worth the under $40.00 this wonderful bag cost. I've purchased lesser quality bags for triple the cost of this bag in the past. Keep an open mind regarding the "smell", it does subside over time, as with any leather product.offering a review that isn't negative, that tries to provide an overview of the quality of this bag, a brief explanation of the "smell" that surrounds this bag, and pictures to give the potential purchasers of this bag a better idea of the size, shape, and color. I wouldn't want to walk around all day in them but for wearing around the office they're perfect. I do wish the shoes didn't have the slight shininess that comes with satin but that's just a personal preference. They fit somewhat narrow, so if you have wide feet these are probably not for you. That being said, these are great shoes for the price and I am happy with my purchase!

Edit: After wearing these roughly three times a week for seven months, I finally threw them out...they smelled horrible! My feet do tend to stink in certain shoes, and these were one of them. It permeated the entire shoe and there was nothing I could do to get rid of the smell, so I finally had to accept that I couldn't wear them anymore. I would be sitting at my desk and able to smell my feet--not a good thing! The shoe itself was still in good shape--my only complaint was that the lining on the bottom inside had started to separate from the sole and would bunch up under my feet, which was annoying. I'm still keeping my four star rating, as the major issue with these was not actually the shoes fault, but my own feet. I won't get them again because of it but I would still recommend them to others as a cheap flat option.

column13: Design keeps the tounge from falling to one side but can be a bit tight.
column14:
I got these shoes in hopes that their design would solve the problem I have always had of the tounge of my shoe falling to one side. Because these shoes don't really have a tounge because they are all one piece they definitely did the trick. They are comfortable and look really cool with a pair of dark jeans cuffed up. I constantly get compliments on them and love that they are light and for fitted to my feet to the point sometimes it doesn't feel like I have shoes on. The soles of these shoes also flex amazingly unlike a cheap running shoe would.

I do have to say though that due to their integrated tounge design they have two problems:
1.) When I am inactive and wearing these and my heart rate is normal they cut off circulation to my feet and my feel get numb. This is because they are tight around the ankle area and top of the foot.
2.)Again because of the tightness around the ankle they can be difficult to squeeze on. I have partially broken the backs of them getting my feet into them. They have loops on the back like most shoes, but one of mine has torn off due to the force put on it when pulling the shoes on.

column13: I like these shoes a lot because they are very extremely ...
column14:
I like these shoes a lot because they are very extremely comfortable. It feels like wearing a very padded soft cloudy sock! However, I have only had them for four months and some of the painted black stripe on the sole has worn off (though I do wear these every single day). Also, the shoe is advertised to have something to prevent foot odors, but if I don't wear socks my feet still get smelly ... I still have to wear socks. I have washed these once in the washing machine and they came out looking great. They also make a funny suction cup unpopping sound when I walk on lab flooring, but that does not bother me.

EDIT: The sound my shoe makes when walking on the lab floors are actually annoying. I would not recommend these shoes if you work in a lab setting or anywhere where the floor is coated with that sheen that makes it easy to wipe up spills.. It's embarrassing when people hear me coming and I only wear these shoes now If I know I will be in the office for most of the day.

I bought a size 7 when I usually wear a 7.5. The only other size 7 shoes I have are Clarks which I also think run large.

column14:
BEWARE: they are SMALL. Nothing bad about it, just take .5 size bigger. I have a 7.5, I fit perfectly in a 8. I read previous reviews and ordered an 8, and they are perfect... 7.5 would not have fit.

For the shoes themselves, you get what you paid for. I'm not saying this as a critic.. just a truth. Great casual shoes, really cheap.
Not 5stars because they look plastic-ish, so I bet they would smell pretty fast (even if they are light and your feet can breathe a lot in them), and since they are kinda cheap, I would not put them in the washer like I do with other shoes, but need to wash them on the sink which is annoying and less efficient.

YAY :) They are good shoes, really comfortable, good for walking in like paved / really good roads / trails, stay home, go groceries, or go to school/work on a casual day. Given they are only $25, they do an awesome job for these activities. This is what I got the shoes for, so I'm happy.
NAY :( If you are committed about running, and plan to use them frequently and for a long time, or if you are looking for some hiking shoes, this just are not good enough. I'd suggest to pay the money Nike asks for.

column6: Ray-Ban Square Sunglasses
column13: Totally Cheaper Quality Than My Original Ones!
column14: I'm almost positive these are fake! I have a pair I got from Nordstrom about 4 years ago. Unfortunately the arm broke off and I lost it.  I was finally able to make another investment and purchase these again because I loved them so much, and I was thrilled when I found them almost $100 cheaper on amazon. Even though there are some bad reviews, for the most part they are good. I purchased them and received them same day. I was sooo excited! Then I opened the box and immediately knew something was off. The creaking is horrible and they are definitely lighter than my other pair. The arms have a seam down the middle which my real pair does not have, and one arm doesn't touch when placed on a flat surface. It is the best knockoff I've ever seen, so I don't know whether to just keep them and save the $100 (because no one else will know) or send them back to get a real pair from SGH or Nordstrom. Someone had a good point in their review saying that RayBan backs up the authenticity of any glasses sold by Amazon and that they are an authorized dealer...but they might have found a way to make 2 different sets. The internet discounted ones and the high end brick and mortar sunglasses. China vs Italy... It's a shame. I was really looking forward to these and now I'm torn.

column6: pediped Sahara Originals Fisherman Sandal (Infant/Toddler)
column13: Easier to put on than expected
column14:
Recently bought these so that we had a pair of sandals for our year old son. The shoes is sized as expected (based on size charts) but I've noticed that Pediped shoes tend to run a little wider than other brands (like Robeez), so we have a little bit of extra room in that aspect. That wasn't a huge surprise to me though because we've had other shoes in this brand before. We accepted the extra width because I love the sole of the shoe. It is very flexible, but still feels thick enough to provide a little bit more protection from pokes when walking on uneven surfaces. The toe of the shoe is very tough also, so imagine that it would hold up well if your child is still primarily crawling (ours walks so can't say for sure).

I was pleased to find that the shoe opened up better than I expected, making it easier to put on. The strap is only permanently attached on one side of the shoe and then attaches with Velcro to both the top/middle of the shoe and the other side. This also allows a little more flexibility on how tight the shoe is around the ankle. I was a little nervous about them rubbing based on other reviews, but have found that we don't have a problem with it. Our son is pretty small (3rd percentile), but I am careful to make sure that I don't Velcro the ankle strap too tight. I have noticed that he sometimes will have a small red mark on his ankle after wearing, but it goes away shortly after taking off the shoe, much like the elastic in a sock ankle can sometimes leave a temporary mark. When wearing with socks, I don't notice any marks, but they could be hidden by the sock itself and/or masked by the sock marks. Either way, because it doesn't seem to bother him and it goes away quickly, I am not worried about it.

column6: New Balance Men's MW411 Health Walking Shoe
column13: Great shoe but needs better glue on sole
column14: I have bought and worn 4 pair of these MW411 walking shoes.  I love the fit and feel.  For fitness, I used to run and wear running shoes but now, as I'm getting older (late 50s), I try to walk as much as I can every day.  My goal is to walk 5 miles a day and I'd say I come pretty close to that.  So my point is I walk a lot in these shoes.  My concern is I don't get full use out of these shoes due to poor bonding of the glue between the sole and shoe body.  Every single pair has failed in the exact same way.  The bottom separates from the body at/near the toe area then the separation gradually gets worse until the whole sole is separated down to the middle of my foot.  At that point, I throw them away and buy another pair.  I haven't tried gluing the sole back to the body as I've seen in other reviews.  The shoes fail at about the 4-5 month point for me.  Given my walking habits, that's perhaps 500 to 600 miles walked.  So I can't fault the shoe entirely.  That's a lot of miles!  But I do think New Balance should recognize this defect and use better glue.  I'd like to wear a hole in a pair or have the sole wear thin just once instead of watching what looks like a perfectly good pair of shoes come unglued!  My plan is to try another brand of walking shoe when the pair I have fails ... the soles are already starting to separate ... again!

column6: Desertwolf Vintage Canvas Tote Bags - Hobo Bag - Cross Body Handbags with Shoulder Strap - Fit 12\ Laptop"
column14:
For a compact cross body bag this one holds up pretty decently from a style and functional standpoint. With its canvas construction and compact sizing this one easily contours to your body and thus looks good as a cross body satchel with the bag itself anchored near your lower back.

At 12.4\\\ x 11.7\\\\\" sizing is definitely on the lean side but the size is adequate to hold a 10\\\\\" iPad in a hard case, a book or two, some magazines, keys, wallet, pens, etc. With the brown canvas and leather accent styling the bag looks suitable for both men and women although to make it more fitting for my style I trimmed off the lower leather belt strap which gives it a cleaner, more rugged look.

There are some branding labels that are not clearly presented on the product page. The little leather strip front and center is labeled as 'Andeliya' while embossed on the lower leather belt strap (the portion I stripped off) is the phrase \\\\\"andeliya xiu xian bag.\\\\\" Overall though, this is well constructed bag with a series of mini pockets to stash your goodies (product sample provided for review)."

column13: I really liked this boot - at first
column14: I really liked this boot - at first.  It got me to some nice places in comfort, kept my feet dry, and did well.  But LONG before the soles got too worn, the soles started to separate from the boot!  I would think this is a defect - the bonding between the boot and the sole should not be this bad.  A friend of mine with the same boot had the exact same problem (hers completely came off during a hike, and had to use duct tape to hold it on for the trail out!  I went here and see there are others with the separation problem - and it looks like this happens all too often - this is not acceptable!  I would be OK if the soles wore out, but not this...  This is far too expensive of a product to be made this poorly.  Shame!

column6: Kipling Discover S Wheeleed Luggage
column14:
I purchased this and the small Darcey at the same time to replace an old Samsonite carry-on and decided to return this one and keep the Darcey. I was looking for a roomy, lightweight case with exterior pockets (specifically a pocket big enough for documents, magazines, etc). Most of the time my only luggage is my carry-on even on extended international trips so durability was also very important. This bag fulfilled most of my criteria, but ultimately was not the right one for me.

Pros:
-Lightweight
-Durable Kipling nylon
-Can pack a whole lot
-Multiple interior compartments
-Multiple exterior pockets

Cons:
-Duffle straps are an inconvenience when you need to access the main compartment quickly. I understand this is "duffle" bag, but due to the dimensions I would have been wheeling this most of time (if not all the time)
-Exterior pockets are small; good for toiletries and packing a lot of smaller items. My personal preference is to have a large exterior compartment.
-2-wheels; this is also a matter of personal preference but I found the Discover less smooth and less maneuverable than the Darcey spinner
-Seems a tad larger than standard carry-on, especially if it were completely packed.

I did not attempt to actually pack the bag so cannot speak to the stability issues when standing upright, but I can see how that could be an issue with such a lightweight bag that is sitting on 2-wheels.

column6: Reebok Men's Crossfit Lite LO TR Training Shoe
column13: No arch = great for powerlifting, potentially a daily alternative for Chucks.
column14: Overall: These shoes are FLAT with a very small rise to the heel. These are powerlifting shoes (I wear them for squats and deadlifts) but I could see them becoming daily shoes for people who like Chucks but want an updated design. I'm on the verge of ordering several pairs for daily wear to keep these clean for the gym.  My Reebok Crossfit Lite TR (7 Mens) compared to my Converse Chucks (7.5 Mens): Reeboks shoes have a wider toe area that doesn't squish my foot. Reebok's heel is skinnier and has more support (thicker material). Reebok has a padded tongue so you can go looser with the laces and they don't want to flop off. Reebok has "proper length" laces compared to Chucks where I'm double-knotting just so they don't drag on the ground.  I also have a 7.5 pair of Reebok Lite TR high tops but they are too long. Turns out the extra .5 size in Chucks I wear is specifically to get the extra width I need. No worries, the 7.5 Reeboks are in the closet until winter when thicker socks can take up the slack.  UPDATE: I bought a size 7.5 in the low top and they fit perfectly. Maybe the high tops I got were over-sized... Either way, I wear these as everyday shoes now.

column13: So Comfy, but Quality Is an Issue
column14:
These are hands-down, the most comfortable, and "squishy" flip flops around. They have good arch support, too. This is my second pair, however, since my first pair broke where the plastic connects to the foot bed in between the toes. It eventually weakens and then rips off. Standing in water while in these shoes also stretches the plastic out. The other downfall of these flip flops is that they also are prone to "catching" when you walk and the front-most part bends as your foot proceeds to extend forward as you walk (and a bit of a trip). As a result of this, my periwinkle is scuffed with black on the front-most part under the toes. This "catching" also stretches out the bond of the connector piece that attaches to the foot bed, thus weakening it. I'll get black if I buy another pair to avoid this unsightly issue; but then I'd be out another $45...

Oofos needs to engineer a sturdier connection point in between the toes to the foot bed to make these last longer. Very comfortable when they are not broken.

column13: Work fine even though I have bunions.  Very comfortable.  Sizing was perfect for me.
column14: I have bunions, so was a little nervous about reviews saying these are narrow. I thought I'd take a chance, as I could return them.  They are stretchy enough that my bunions are not a problem.  I have also found that they are easy to slip on barefoot, for a quick trip to take the dog out.  I need more ankle support as I get older, and had looked at some more expensive hiking boots that zipped up, thinking they'd be easier to quickly put on and off, but thought I'd start with these because the ratings were so good.  I can slip my feet in these easily and just quickly tie them.  When I'm going to go for a serious walk, I can lace them up more tightly.  But, these have exceeded all of my expectation.  They were also really comfortable right out of the box.  The ankle support is not quite as good as a heavier hiking boot, but good enough, and I love that they're much lighter than my old hiking boots.  I'd buy these again in a heartbeat.  Oh, and I went with my normal size of a 9.5, and they are perfect with or without socks.  I don't wear really thick socks, though.  But, I disagree that you have to buy these more than a 1/2 size bigger, and only then would I do so if you use thick socks, in my opinion.

column14: I read the other reviews and I wear a 9.5 in closed toed shoes and I ordered the 9 and there is still room for a light sock. I normally do not wear socks in sneakers but the placement of the stiff leather Adidas tag on the tongue made them rub the top of my ankle without socks. I added a light sock and problem solved. My shoes came with a coral colored lace- I am going to switch them out for white- personal preference. Overall for less than $20 a solid value! With some minor fussing which I do anyway they are comfy and cute and are a well made shoe.  Would have given 5 stars if they had come with 2 sets of laces like most sneakers do. column6: Teva Women's Original Sandal
column13: Design problems with length of ankle strap (too short) and foot strap (too long).
column14: Generally a good shoe for the river/lake/beach or walking around in. Good quality polyester uppers. Rubber bottoms are ok (I've had mine about 2 mos and they have a gauge in them from getting caught on something I don't remember). Textured footbed is great, helps keep you from slipping when walking in water. Was a little scratchy for a day or two but comfy after that. Shoe feels too big in the strap across the foot closest to the toes- there is so much room the shoe drags/scrapes the sidewalk often enough to be annoying when lifting your foot to walk. Conversely the ankle strap is either way too short or the straps connecting the ankle strap to the sole are too short...if the strap was actually around the ankle the size would be fine, but because it is below the ankle bone, that's a pretty wide place, and I have average-size ankles. Because the straps are too short (there is about a 1/2 inch - 1 inch of exposed velcro), when you sit with your ankles crossed and then uncross them, the exposed sticky velcro has attached itself to the decorative polyester upper ankle strap on the front of the other shoe, pilling and fuzzing a material that should otherwise be durable. I bought the mosaic vintage indigo and like the color. Maybe teva should consider some beta testing and have some people wear the shoe before manufacturing a zillion of them with such an inherent flaw? I have mixed feelings on this shoe- comfortable but the cost implies better execution.

column13: Very cute but hard and unsupportive footbed and feel like heels not like wedges (in terms of stability)
column14: I usually wear size 8.5 in sandals but the size 9 in these fit me fine. The sandals are a gorgeous vibrant orange color that is still sophisticated. And the design is flattering and sexy but keeps your foot snug on all sides. Unfortinately the footbed was SO hard and inflexible! I felt like I was wearing wooden clogs. Now, I must say that I do have VERY picky feet and high arches so usually I buy expensive comfort sandals from Born and Clarks so may be I am too spoiled. But I didn't think I could wear this for more than an hour. Also, I was scared I'd twist my ankle in them as I felt a bit unstable. The wedge tapers down in the back quite a bit and they are overall very high so if you are not used to wearing tall thinner heels these might be scary for you. I have never worn skinny high heels. But I can manage well-made thicker heels and these did not feel safe for me at all. In short, despite being a wedge they felt like a regular heel to me. Combined with the hard footbed I just did not think I would wear them much so I returned them. However, IF you don't have picky arches AND are comfortable in regular high heels and are not intimidated by 3.5in height do give these a try as in terms of style they are to die for.

column14: I love Sperry shoes. In fact, they are the only flat flop flips that I purchase now...and I grew up in Hawaii where flip flops are a way of life!!!  Thus, I consider myself a flip flop connoisseur! So, why Sperry? 1. They are consistently true to size. 2. The quality of the shoe is excellent. 3. The color does not come off on my foot (this is a big problem for me with cheap flip flops). 4. They last. I bought my first pair 3 years ago and still have them and wear them. I live in flip flops as much as possible so they "get a beating and keep on ticking" ...  okay, they don't tick! 5. I have high arches and these shoes are very comfortable but I think any type of arch would be fine in these flip flops. 6. They are washable. 7. I don't feel the earth. In cheap flip flops I could feel every pebble; the cushion on the Sperry protects your feet. Finally, I own 6 pairs of their flip flops and 2 pairs of their loafers. I absolutely love them all. I have never had a blister. The first time.e that I wore them they felt like a pair of old comfy shoes!

column6: Polarized Aviator P27 Sunglasses by JiMarti
column13: These are great sunglasses for the value
column14:
These are great sunglasses for the value. The polarization works as well as much more expensive glasses I have purchased, and they look almost as good as well. I bought them after mistaking them for Ray Bans on a friend, and now multiple people have asked me "Are those Ray Bans?" My response: "Ray Bans? Peh. These are Jimartis, brother! If you don't know Jimarti, you don't know jack."

I've lost a lot of friends this way.

They did break a bit when I stepped on them, but I would say that's more my fault. My friend's pair eventually broke in the same way, though, and he did not step on them. In both cases, the little nose clippy thing fell off, but mine still rest on my nose pretty comfortably.

Overall, for $40, they're a great value. If you're like me, and you lose or step on a lot of your sunglasses, this is a good pair to buy that you won't hate to replace.

column6: DAWGS Womens Arch Support Z Sandals
column13: ROLL THE DICE FOR THESE DAWGS AND YOU JUST MIGHT GET LUCKY
column14: I own two pair of Dawgs now and love the prints. I have the multi-colored-floral ones and the red, white, and blue ones. People who see them for the first time always comment positively about them. My findings are that I wear a size 7 1/2 Medium, and have ordered shoes online for years and never had to return a pair. Having read on several sites that they run a bit large, I ordered size 7, and length-wise they fit perfectly. However, the Z-straps are somewhat loose, and there's no real arch support. I expected the width of the straps would run smaller, since I was ordering a half size shorter than what I normally wear, but this is not the case. They fit me somewhat loose, so I can't wear them over a couple of hours or they start rubbing my feet. However, I read here that some people think they run small, so that means there is poor quality control at the factory in China. This is a real downer, and no doubt costs Dawgs some revenue by people who don't want to deal with returns, as they aren't free, like they are on most shoe sites. I, myself, went on this site to order another pair in a solid color this time, but I won't, as I'm afraid I might get a pair that is too large, too small, or too short. All of these have been listed as complaints here. My opinion is that, if you take a 1/2 size shoe, then order a size down (as I did), and if you have a wide foot or high instep, they will probably fit you very comfortably. But if you normally take a medium or narrow width shoe, then you probably will be unhappy with them. Medium will be loose and narrow won't do at all. If you want to take a 'Dawgs Roulette' shot at fit, then by all means order them. They're cute and reasonably comfortable, but wish I could buy the Canadian version, as I've read here that the footbed is smooth and more comfortable than the 'pebbly' USA ones.

I bought some washable terry cloth inserts from Pedag on amazon and have been using them inside instead of socks and it looks and feels great. I think you could probably wear these all day if you don't need a lot of support, but I just wear them in 2-3 hour bursts usually. They seem well made and true to size. column6: LaCrosse Men's Tallgrass Square Toe 11 Inch Work Boot
column13: The square-toed Tallgrass style is better for wide feet than the western-toe Tallgrass style .... I really like 'em.
column14: This review is an update to the one I did in midsummer of 2015, just after purchasing these boots. I've worn these boots on an everyday basis since the weather got cold enough in November, and my consensus is ‚Ä¶ they're all-day comfortable. They fit well, feel good and look good.  I had to buy this pair in a size one whole size up from what I usually wear. Just before I bought these boots in July, I'd  returned a new pair of LaCrosse's Tallgrass "western-toed" boots similar to these because they were way too small and not wide enough, even though I bought the WIDE in my usual size. The LaCrosse sizes for this boots style seem to run smaller by a half or full size than I usually buy. The square toe version, in WIDE, gave me the width I needed.  They seemed a little long in the toe at first with the square style toe, and the heel of the sole sticks back a bit farther than any other boots I've worn. BUT: Both those factors have turned out to be solid pluses.  First, I'm a motorcycle rider. The longer toe gives me much better feel and control for the shifting and rear brake levers. Improved contact and traction at the toe, without too much bulk. The extra toe length protects my foot from impacts from the front, but not the top, since the version of this boot I purchased does not have a steel or composite toe. I've gotten used to the longer toe for just walking around; it's a non-issue.  Second, when it comes time to pull these boots off at the end of the day, that extra little bit of lip on the rear of the sole's heel gives a perfect catch to hold the boot's heel down while you pull your foot up and out. You can step on that lip with your other toe to hold it down, or use a regular boot-jack, or hook it under the edge of the top step on the stairs like I do. If the boots don't fit you too tightly, they'll come off easily this way. Nice for those of us with a little bit of belly, like me. Not having to crunch down over your beer gut to lace your work boots is one of the best reasons to buy a pull-on boot.  If you haven't worn a Welllington style pull-on leather boot before, they take a little getting used to at first. Your foot settles a little farther forward on the sole than in lace-up boots, and if the fit is right, this is not a problem, just different. If they fit right, you shouldn't have to pull really hard to get them off, but they should't be so loose that you foot slides around, or you can just slide you foot up and out without having to hold the heel down. You should have to pull up on the side loops to get them on, but NOT have to pull really hard.  The other thing I've come to like about these boots is the feel of the interior sole right under my foot: under the heel and the ball of your foot. There's some nice comfy give under these pressure points, but still excellent support.  I like everything about these boots, the western styling, but with a regular low, workbook heel, and all the features I've already mentioned. Nice work LaCrosse. I'd buy them again, if mine ever wear out.

column6: Teva Women's Original Universal Sandal
column13: These shoes are a must for people with flat feet!
column14:
Okay so a little bit of a background; I was in desperate near of a supportive type of shoe for college since I will be walking around A LOT.
I dont have a very defined ach and my feet are pretty much flat, so I wanted a very cushiony shoe that did not have a very defined arch.

Let me tell you, Tevas are the way to go! It is so comfortable and when I first put them on, I could tell there was no "breaking in" necessary. There was no chafing for me at all and the foot bed is extremely comfy. The 2nd time I wore them, I had em on all day as I spent the day shopping and it was very comfortable! My feet werent sore as they usually are when I wear shoes with no support.

I was worried about getting a 10 at first. My feet are usually a size 9.5, but I don't have short toes so I decided to size up, which was a really good idea. They fit perfectly: not too wide at all, length is perfect (about a quarter inch of space in the front and back)
I highly suggest sizing down if you're normally a half size know you have short toes, and up if you have normal/long toes.

column6: Miz Mooz Women's Astrid Fisherman Sandal
column14:
I loved these. They looked great with dresses and pants and were reasonably comfortable. Then, after having them for a month and a half, I was wearing them and felt a sharp poking/scratching in my ankle. A sharp metal wire (!!) had worked its way out of the bottom edge of the heel strap. Checking the other shoe, the same wire was beginning to come out of that one as well. The shoes still look brand new, with no obvious wear on the soles or insoles. This shouldn't have happened. And they shouldn't have been made this way.
I tried calling the contact number for Miz Mooz. The phone rang about 10 times and the connection ended with a fast busy signal. I then read another review that they had a poor warranty/customer service record. Fortunately, Amazon came through for me and my sandals are on their way back. While I'm very grateful to Amazon, I won't be buying Miz Mooz shoes again. Great design, terrible quality.

column6: Salomon Men's Evasion Mid GTX Hiking Shoe
column14:
Living in the northwest, we look for a couple important features in our hiking footwear:

- Waterproof
- Provide comfort in hot and dry temperatures, as well as freezing and snowy climates
- Excellent fit and durable

Many hiking boots can claim all of the above, but what truly set these apart in my opinion is the fit. I think this is definitely worth the higher price point, and is what separated these from the lower priced alternatives. It's like a perfect mold to my foot, and each step feels flawless. I would absolutely recommend these as an option that breaks into the high end spectrum of boots.

column14:

They do a great job of cutting brightness and glare without reducing clarity or muddying up the view. I find that many inexpensive sunglasses do just that, you put them on and you find you can't see the finer details of what you are looking at. I wore these glasses all day on a pontoon boat on a very sunny day and found that they were comfortable and that I didn't get a headache from the sun bouncing off the water. Win-win!
I received these complimentary glasses in order for me to review, but I WILL buy them again.

column13: Turn your regular shoes into dance shoes!
column14:
Last summer, I dislocated my kneecap and quickly learned that the type of shoes that you wear in a Zumba dance class is an important factor to avoiding injuries. There are a lot of slides and spins in Zumba and wearing your regular tennis shoes can cause a lot of avoidable knee pain. These slip-on dancers are the perfect solution to turn your regular shoes into dance shoes!

Simply slip them over your shoes and position them where your foot would pivot when spinning on the floor. You might have to play around with position to get the perfect fit. I love that they help you move more easily when dancing, but still give you traction from your shoes during the times when you need it.

By the time I was able to walk back to the dressing room it had rubbed my foot so badly I developed a large blister before I even walked down the aisle.  I did have a pair of back up shoes (Blue by Betsey Johnson Bow, purchased for the reception), but was only able to wear them long enough for the ceremony due to the pain from the aforementioned blister.  I spent my reception in flip flops instead of the other pair of Betsy Johnson heels I purchased.

column13: Very good hiking shoes - trail runners?  not so much
column14:
I can see these being a very good hiking shoe for cool, wet weather. As a trail runner, they're too heavy and clunky for my tastes. Once you get used to running in minimalist shoes, everything else feels like you're walking on stilts. Having said that, the reason I got these was to use them as 3-season hiking shoes for places where it hurts to wear my thin-soled low-profile shoes. I say 3-season because they're way too hot for summertime wear. The construction is very solid and the fit is good, but not great. I like a wide toe box and tight heel cup and these have neither. These have sufficient room up front, but it's not toe-spreading heaven like a Merrell barefoot. Also, the lacing provides lots of adjustability to size the shoe as you move from thin to thick socks.

Overall these are a great value. For someone who likes more cushioning and less ground feel they would be a great choice. Now I'm just waiting for cold, sloppy weather to really use them.

column13: Great Summer Sandal for Active Three Year Old - compared with See Kai Run, StrideRite and Keen's
column14:
My mom ordered these sandals/shoes from Amazon for my super active 3.5 year old daughter. I normally purchase See Kai Run, StrideRite and Keen's for my daughter.

These sandals are appropriately priced for its quality on Amazon in the $20 range. The leather is nice (not too soft and not too rigid) -- I used to sell products in the equestrian market and I am familiar with various qualities of leather. Stitching looks like it should hold and all of the lines are straight. The sandals are a Velcro closure - this is good for my toddler, but I'll be curious how long the Velcro will last. While the leather is nice, like I said, there are some areas where it is not straight and has a "little wave" in it. Only a very particular person may notice such a discrepancy and it should not affect the quality of the overall sandal. There are also some minor glue marks (glue squeezed out from the sole area), but it also seems minor.

The sole of the shoe is grippy and super flexible. If you don't want super flexible, don't order these sandals. The footbed is smooth without bumps (like in less expensive shoes from big box stores) and seem comfy.

My daughter is tall for her age and has a foot to match her height - she recently grew into size 11 by See Kai Run or 11.5 by Stride Rite. These sandals are a size 11 and fit just right. They are also slightly wide, but that works very well for my daughter. I don't know if the sandals would be too wide for a very narrow foot. I definitely do not recommend these for a super narrow heel or super slim ankle!

I like the sandals because my daughter can run and climb in them, plus they look "sporty nice" with her shorts, skirts and dresses.

Overall, pretty good. With the glue showing and leather not straight, I've taken a star away because the sandal is not of the highest quality. I still favor See Kai Run and Keen's (which are in the $30-50 range), but I might just order this pair again next season.again next season.

column6: Shoe Goo Repair Adhesive for Fixing Worn Shoes or Boots, Clear, 3.7-Ounce Tube
column13: Unbeatable general purpose shoe/boot maintenance material
column14: This  is essentially a very viscid contact cement. As such, it's an excellent product for *preventive* maintenance on shoes and boots, to prevent delamination for example. It's also a good repair product, to stick part of a sole or heel back on, or to seal a puncture in a shoe or boot. There are stronger glues which you can use strictly to glue things together, but as a general maintenance material, Shoe Goo is excellent. I use it to build up the tips of my dog's boots, which wear off quickly as the dog walks. For purposes like that, it's best to use *three* coats of the Shoe Goo, allowing each coat to dry thoroughly before applying the next.

column6: Tapp Collections™ Multi-pocket Nylon Purse Insert Organizer
column14:
It's just OK. The material is very soft and folds over on itself, which makes it very hard to use unless you set your purse down on a hard surface and straighten up the two zippered pockets to get into them. If my purse is on my shoulder, I have to struggle to get my wallet back into the large middle section because the zipper pockets have collapsed into the center section I need something that works on the fly. The zippers don't work very smoothly. You have to straighten out the zipper to get it to work. The two handles stick up in the middle and get in the way. I had high hopes for this, but no. If someone could somehow make this organizer more rigid, it would be a winner. There should also be a leash to hook your keys on. So disappointing.

Not willing to give up, I purchased a very similar Travel Smart organizer that is made of clear plastic. It looks just like the Tapp C. above. The plastic does make the organizer more sturdy. However, anything else that is plastic, such as a water bottle, sticks to the organizer making it a struggle to put anything in or remove anything from the plastic pockets. With some minor changes, these could be excellent products.

column6: Fossil Mercer Top-Zip Work Bag
column14: We replaced my husband's canvas military surplus shoulder bag (falling apart) with this Fossil Mercer and it's night and day. It's a gorgeous bag with lots of storage while maintaining clean lines and a modest profile. The leather feels fantastic, but it's got enough heft to make it feel durable too. The stitching and detailing is well done with no popped or loose threads, and no scuffs to the leather. The compartments are zippered, open, zippered. The two outer zipper sections have multiple pockets for accessories, and the center (open) section with snap tab fits our 14" Alienware laptop with no issues. While this means it's easily accessed, it does mean that if you get caught out in the rain, your laptop is vulnerable to the elements. If it weren't for that this would be a five-star bag, no question. This bag is an investment in a quality tool that looks smart in the workplace, but transitions easily to weekend use too.

column6: Thorogood Men's  6\ Moc-Toe Wedge-Heel Non-Safety Boot"
column13: Quality that reminds you of a bygone era
column14:
You will notice a huge difference between these boots and Chinese made junk sold by other well known name brands who put profits ahead of doing what's right. These are made by Americans who care about quality. Make sure you buy at least 1/2 size smaller than you usually order. It's not that these run small, it's that the leather stretches over time to give you a boot custom fit to your foot. Thorogood can do this because they use a high quality leather - think high end baseball gloves for your feet. Once they break in, you'll never go back. The cheap leathers used by offshore manufacturers don't perform like this so continue buying those boots too big for your feet and hope for the best.

These are my third pair. The others haven't worn out, I just have one pair for dirty heavy work, one for standing all day work, and another for wearing around town.

column6: adidas Performance Men's Speed Trainer 2 Training Shoe
column13: So far, I love them... DEFINITELY RUN SMALL COMPARED TO NIKE, ORDER 1 SIZE UP!!!
column14:
I'm a big fan of the new "Trainer" shoe craze thats blown up. Up until now I have rocked the Nike Free 3.0, but their designs have gotten a little out of control, so I thought I'd try the Adidas version. Glad I did. Cheaper than Nike, just as comfy (if not more so, time will tell), and not quite as "over-designed".

I wear a 16 in Nike, Asics, Adidas Originals, but apparently not in new Adidas. The 16 was very small. All 5 toes were deforming the end of the shoe. Aside from them being to small, they were super light, very cushy sole, and seemed to have great arch support. On top of very long feet, i also have very narrow and flat feet to boot. These run on the narrow side, and that is great for me.

I returned the 16's and ordered the 17's. It was annoying that the 16's were Prime, and the 17's weren't prime and $7 more expensive, 24 hours later.

Solid shoe so far.

column13: The right boot had a thick piece of leather backing the eyelets that wasn't properly sewn down and it rolled back causing a pres
column14:
I gave these boots the benefit of 2 stars mostly because I had appreciated the quality of shoes I had purchase from Timberland in the past. Something has changed in their quality control. The right boot had a thick piece of leather backing the eyelets that wasn't properly sewn down and it rolled back causing a pressure point felt like an eyelet was digging into my foot. The left boots leather behind the heel cup was either to soft or not taut enough, it wrinkled causing a blister. About an hour was as long as I could stand to wear these boots. I gave them about 4 tries each about a month apart. The materials seemed high quality but something was amiss in the construction.

I called Timberland and they told me to send the them in (at my expence ~$25). They sent back the boots and said they were to worn for the warranty. I had just wanted them made wearable. These boots, which I had worn for about 4 hours over 6 months, had no wear on the sole and only a few scuff marks. These were boots, I didn't treat them as dress shoes. I was more interested in the wear and comfort. I had never had to deal with Timberland's consumer department in the past, so I don't know if my experience was typical. I was disappointed in their response.

column14:
I haven't had these shoes long so I will have to come back and update at a later time. They have a really great look to these shoes. They also seem to be good quality. I normally wear a 12 in most shoes. These cramped my toes because of how narrow the tip of the shoe goes. By the end of day 1 wearing them at the office, one of my feet was killing me in the toes. I decided to hold out in hopes that they would stretch out a little, and they did. The next time I wore them they gave more room and the pain was nowhere near the same. The third time a little more. I do like the shoe for the rice and got a lot of compliments on them. They have rubber soles so they're quiet when you walk. They don't give you the hard sole dress shoe sound.

I also don't think the shoes breathe very well which is my biggest complaint. If you have wide feet like me, you may not want to consider these shoes at all (as I don't seem them available in wide at this point in time). With Amazon you can always return the shoe upfront if it doesn't fit. I took a gamble and I'm happy. They've loosened up and look great. I just hope they hold up for a while.

column6: Merrell Men's Encore Bypass Slip-On Shoe
column13: Do not breathe well, mesh does not penetrate to interior of shoes
column14:
Point:
---Comfortable fit, seem well-made (duh, they're Merrells)
---Breathe marginally better than shoes with full-leather-uppers
Counterpoint:
---"Mesh" descriptions imply the mesh is solid straight through to the inside of the shoe, but it is not. This might have been okay, but
---Inner lining of shoe doesn't breathe well
Conclusion:
---Great shoes for Summer in upper Catskills, avoid if you live south of Pennsylvania, and if you live south of Virginia, there's a good chance nothing much will help you stay cool outside anyway...
-------
If you live anywhere with temperatures regularly above 85 Fahrenheit, don't buy these. The "mesh" uppers on these are mostly aesthetic, and rest atop a solid layer of cloth. I understand the description lists a cloth lining. However, if the lining is primarily an insulator and does not, in fact, "breathe" well (as advertised) the mesh is of little to no value.

I thought I might be imagining it, because surely the mesh topper wouldn't be inhibited by a single layer of cloth as long as it breathes well, right?

So I ran a little experiment comparing the Merrells to my (dark-grey) running shoes in terms of how well they stay cool. To ensure reasonable control, I stood outside in both pairs of shoes in direct sunlight for 3 minutes before getting into my (already-cool) car to test. Placing my feet in the Merrels and then under the AC unit in my car, it took 3 minutes before I could even *begin* to feel any of the coolness underneath. I did the same experiment with my running shoes and started feeling the coolness on my toes within 30s.

column14: If you have ever broken in a pair of Doc Martens or a pair of Fyre boots you will already be familiar with the "stiff" leather that so many mention in their reviews; this is a sign of a high quality and long-lasting pair of shoes. It is also helpful to make sure to read all the reviews for the style you are interested in buying and measure your feet per the size guide on the SH site to make sure you secure the proper size. It is very helpful. These boots are beautiful! The Bordeaux/Nature is a great combo! They do seem to run a little small, but I did expect that per other reviews. My feet are average size 7's, medium to sIightly narrow and bought these in a size 38 - perfect. Maybe a little loose once fully broken in. I have been breaking them in inside (because it's summer). Today was the 4th time I wore them for a few hours (with socks). My feet are starting to mold to the shoes now and they are pretty comfortable. Only 2 trouble spots for me - the width of my feet are a little tight and achy after an hour or so but going away now. And the ankle area on my left foot was a little sore yesterday, but not today.  Not hard to get on at all - use the pull tab in the back! Take it easy breaking them in and they'll last you forever!! Don't expect to wear them out of box for hours without discomfort!

column13: wanted to like them, but very difficult fit
column14:
It's a nice idea and I wish it would have worked better for me. Unfortunately, since the shape didn't quite fit my shoe perfectly it caused little parts of the insole to crinkle up over time, creating sharp hard lumps in my footbed that did not feel good to walk on. By the end of the month I had to discard them because they were too uncomfortable to walk on any more, and they could not be simply smoothed out or cut to size like a normal insole (at least I don't have the tools for that).

Overall, I think these are a great idea, but in practice they should either be smaller than the size of your shoe so that the edges dont get pushed up causing sharp spots in the footbed, or you need to have to tools to precisely cut these to the shape of your shoe interior which I think would be difficult to do, but doable with enough dedication. I wanted to like these and I could certainly use the shoe freshening of this idea, but they just didn't work for me.

column14: UPDATE 9/9/2016 - Do not buy these shoes!  While they are adorable and simple, they will absolutely kill your feet. I have no idea how I walked up and down the aisle.  I had to take them off as soon as I got to the reception and put flip flops on.  These shoes now sit in the back of my closet and will soon be heading to Goodwill.  Do yourself a favor and order a better pair of shoes, even at a higher price.   They are a great purchase for the price and the simplicity of them cannot be beat.  I'll be wearing these with a grey bridesmaids dress for an upcoming wedding and while they aren't entirely comfortable, they are better than many other strappy sandals I've worn.  The bottom strap is a little tight around my toes, but I'm sure with time it will loosen up and become more comfortable.  I'm happy with the purchase overall and would recommend them.

column13: High-quality, flexible, and very light but tough
column14: This soling material is [[ASIN:B00AAWGA5C SoleTech Soling Material #18C Cloud Eva 18 Iron Soling Material - Color Black]]. One side is very smooth, the other textured for better adhesion when cemented. I have been using this type of material for soles for hand-made footwear for decades. I have recently learned that gluing small patches of very thin Vibram sheet to the wear regions (ball and heel) vastly increases the life of the soles and substantially reduces chances of slipping on wet, smooth surfaces. The black sole color works well with black or brown shoes.

column6: ASICS Women's GEL-Kayano 21 Running Shoe
column13: Amazingly comfortable, looks awesome, but toe box is NOT bigger - going back to the GT2000
column14: SO bummed!! My last 4 pairs of running sneakers were all Asics - 2 pairs of the GT 1000's and 2 pairs of the GT 2000's, all of which I wore straight into the ground. They were terrific for an overpronator who walks like a damn pigeon (i.e. me!). This time, I wanted to try something new and read lots of amazing reviews about the Kayano 21s, including a mention that they made the toe box bigger from the last model. I fell in love with the turquoise/pink/white color scheme so I snagged a pair... although they are amazingly comfortable from the get-go and look superb, the toe box is in no way, shape or form 'bigger'. I was a size 8 in the GT 1000s & 2000s - with the Kayano 21s, the left shoe fits perfect, but my right big toe keeps hitting the front of the sneaker. NOT comfortable! Though they are not causing any real pain, I could not stop focusing on my right toe hitting the front of the sneaker. A size 8.5 will be too big for my left foot, so I guess I am going back to the GT 2000s :( Same situation happened when I tried to buy a pair of the Gel Nimbus sneakers back in the spring, so be forewarned!!

column6: K-SWISS Men's SI 18 Rannell 2 Fashion Sneaker
column13: There are just a little bit short of being good for seriously running in
column14:
There are just a little bit short of being good for seriously running in. I am slightly overweight. Don't get me wrong - these are nice to run in if I wasn't so heavy, and they are comfortable and treat my feet as well as my Danner work boots, on my feet all day.

I don't expect these to be as durable as work boots, but they are light and breathable and excellent for walking and working. I have a neutral gait, and medium/high arches. My foot is medium wide, and these were comfortable out of the box. The only thing that I would suggest to improve them, would be a different lining in the heel, because it turns into those sand paperish little fabric balls that you get with cheap underwear.

Also, one version of the Rannell has a suede upper forefoot, all the way up to the laces. I really like the mesh piece on my version. First of all, my big toe is covered by the suede toe cap, so durability isn't a concern. Second, the breath-ability of the mesh is a big reason why I wear them. Thirdly, suede really is impractical, and the suede synthetic balance on my version of the Rannells, with the mesh forefoot upper, is a good balance. If I had any more suede to worry about, it would turn me off of the shoe. It's a borderline neutral running shoe, and a great neutral walking shoe for me. More suede, in my opinion, would relegate it to the fashion bin, and for me, there are much more fashionable shoes than this one. The mesh makes it way better for walking and working in, with the suede in there for stylish reinforcement.

column13: And it was a great decision to buy these instead of new shoes
column14:
Bought these after checking around online. I originally was going to buy a pair of walking shoes since I had a business trip that would have me walking through cities for about a week, but I saw that this would be a cheaper option.

And it was a great decision to buy these instead of new shoes!

column6: PRIX DE DRESSAGE Leather Perforated Logo Zip Top Hobo Handbag
column14:
I rarely write a review but this time I have to. I purchased this bag around June 18 so it's probably safe to say I started using it on June 20-ish. One month later the should strap of the bag snapped as I was walking to my office. What's more, it's not the thread holding the leather together that has given up. It's the leather itself that has snapped, looking like what old rotten leather would do. I use this bag for mainly a 13-inch macbook, which is quite light. My last bag, which I purchased with less than $100, has lasted my 6 years and 3 different 15-inch macbook...and that bag is still fine! I merely replaced it out of wanting something new, and ice gone back to it since the new bag broke.

Given this is a lxurary brand name, this is simply unacceptable. A $50 bag should be expected to last more than a month! So I contacted the seller and left a message with pictures of the damaged bag. A week passed and I never heard anything.

I eventually called Amazon and Amazon processed the refund right away. I should mention that I was offered the option of replacement as well, but I was too wary of the product quality from this seller to take that option. So, hail to the excellent service from Amazon, but extremely unacceptable product quality and service quality by this seller. I don't pat $120 for this, nor even if it's a huge discount from the original product price - if it's a fake, please say it in product description!

column6: Clarks Women's Helio Jet Wedge Sandal
column14:
With anticipation I slipped these shoes on as soon as they arrived and took a few steps. The word "wow" came out of my mouth! I had hoped the other reviews were right about this sandal's comfort. They were!
I am the only woman I know that dreads shoe shopping, as I wear a hard-to-find 10 1/2 wide. I can often get away with ordering a 10 in open-toed sandals, though, so I gave these a try. They are wide enough at the front of my foot, and actually narrower at the heel which fits my foot perfectly. They even make my "Herman Munster" feet look smaller! :)
I decided to order the tan/neutral colored ones too, chancing a 9 1/2 wide (because of the $18 price difference with the sizes) and it fit too! I have worn these sandals out for a few hours at a time, and felt no discomfort so far. They seem well made and should last me a few years. And I agree with the other reviews; if you are a tall woman, these sandals won't make you feel like you are towering over everyone else.

column6: UGG Women's Mini Bailey Bow Scallop Boot
column14: I love Uggs. Plain and simple. I could wear them year round, every day, all day!! I had never tried the Mini Bailey Bow before and read reviews that said buy your regular size not a size smaller like most Uggs. I did that, ordered my regular size and unfortunately, had to return them and buy the size down. They were way too large. Once I got the smaller size, they are adorable in a fashion sense and as comfortable as any Uggs are in a practical sense.  The color is delicious and I was not disappointed in any way with these. I would say this about the sizing as I know its always a controversy. If you have ever bought Uggs before and you normally buy a size smaller, stick with buying a size smaller in these. I have Ugg Classic Shorts, Mini, Classic Tall and Adirondacks and Bailey Button. the ONLY one I was ever able to buy my regular size in was the Adirondacks. Every other pair I own, I have always bought a size smaller and been fine with that. I wear them with and without socks and I am fine both ways with the smaller size.

column6: AllhqFashion Women's Split Round Toe Cow Leather Solid Sandals with Flowers and Applique
column14:
These days, it seems hard for me to find shoes that fit my style. I prefer shoes that are feminine, not clunky, and I also want them to be comfortable. My favorite shoe style is a sandal ‚Äì both flat and heeled. I received the AllhqFashion Women's Split Round Toe Cow Leather Solid Sandals with Flowers and Applique last month and was very pleased with the look of these sandals ‚Äì they fit my requirements exactly.

Not only that, but I‚Äôve received a number of compliments every time I‚Äôve worn these shoes.

I mentioned earlier that comfort was a requirement of mine ‚Äì this has become increasingly more important to me as I grow older. I‚Äôm not willing to ‚Äòsuffer‚Äô for fashion any longer and I don‚Äôt think women have to. I‚Äôve worn these shoes for nine hours or more at a time and they‚Äôve felt just fine.

The ‚Äòbuckle‚Äô is a little odd. It looks like a traditional buckle with a post that slips through the hole to fasten, and indeed you can adjust the sandal strap a bit this way, but that is not how the shoe is fastened on your foot. The fastener is actually a little slide bar that slides just behind the buckle and holds firmly. It isn‚Äôt hard to fasten, but it is a little unusual at first.

I am very pleased with this pair of sandals and would recommend it to anyone who is looking for a feminine, flirty pair of flat sandals. I will upload photos of the sandals as well.

I received a free sample of these shoes to test in order to write an honest review.

column14: LOVE the way these look. I bought these for a running shoe, but they do not have enough support for running. They are comfy with the memory foam soles, but I wouldn't call them a high quality shoe, and don't see them lasting as long as others I have. The first time I wore them they felt fine, but the second time they gave me a horrible blister on my right ankle only. So much so, I looked down after my jog and saw my ankle was covered in blood! I had felt discomfort but though I just needed to break them in a little. I examined both shoes to see if the right shoe was different and what could be rubbing, but both looked fine. Waited for my ankle to heal and tried again, same thing. I ended up using them for work, where I wear very thick socks. That resolved the rubbing issue, when I wear very thick socks and don't jog in them they don't rub. I think in the future I just need to stay away from this brand, they just aren't very good quality.

column6: Columbia Men's Woodburn Mid Hiking Boot
column14:
It's a very nice hiking boot. I bought them in preparation for a camping trip that would include various hikes. I wore the boots the week prior and noticed that I could wear it all day with out any discomfort. They're light and the fit is very nice, especially for boots. Being a retired Marine, I'm no longer lean (260#) and my feet have seen the ill effects of wearing combat boots extensively.

On the hikes, these boots did exceptionally well. The terrain was mixed sand/dirt, basalt and granite. Grip was very good on the climb and I was able to descend with little discomfort on my knees or heels.

I would recommend these boots.

column6: Reef Women's Mallory Scrunch Flip-Flop
column13: I always buy the super thick soled
column14: I always buy the super thick soled, ultra comfortable Reefs, sometimes men's sizes, and I wanted something that made me feel feminine and hippyish.  I love the look of these.  I do wish they had a thicker sole with more arch support, but I willingly made the trade off in favor of cute.  I am usually an 11 but Reef tends to put the toe separator in the same place on the women's 10 and 11 so buying a ten left my toes in the same place and meant that my foot entirely filled out the shoe with no extra room in the back, which is okay by me.  My feet are wide, so I don't understand the comments about wide feet, but there are many ways for a foot to be wide I guess.  What I do know is that when fit is important to you you shouldn't get cloth anywhere that touches your feet.  You can always stretch leather but you can't stretch cloth, so I can understand why the folks with complaints couldn't get their shoes to fit right.  Anyway, I think they're cute...but go try them on before you buy!

column13: great slipper, but the size is a bit tricky
column14: For me, the large was too small (I sent them back), even though I wear a 10 1/2 shoe or at most, an 11. So I got this in the extra large size and it's truly an extra large, probably true to its 12 - 13 description. It's a little too large for me, but that's okay. I've had a pair of these for years and really love them, and they do shrink a tiny bit if you wash them in hot water and dry on high in the dryer. They've always been very comfortable and provide much more arch support than most slippers, which is why I bought them. So if you're looking at the large size, keep in mind that at least for me, they seemed to run a bit small. But the extra large size is probably pretty accurately described. They're very comfortable and reasonably warm, not likely to make your feet sweat. My old pair are probably 4 years old and you would never know by looking at them. They have held up great. The new pair look just as sturdy and I am therefore expecting them to hold up as well.

column6: Salewa Men's MS MTN Trainer Mid GTX Hiking Shoe
column14: I hiked in the original Mountain Trainers , Size 8.5, and the fit was perfect with the double insole and both Smartwool Trekking and Hiker socks. The brown/yellow MS Mountain Trainer's last has less volume and is slightly smaller even using a single insole.The boot consumed my full foot, front to back, with my toes touching the front.  I am returning the 8.5s for size 9. Size 8.5 is listed as a Euro size 41. The 9 is listed as a 42. The original model was fantastic hiker, heaver than the newer model. Update: I ordered the brown/yellow boot in a size 9 and the fit was too large even with both insoles in the boot. Amazon dropped the price on the pewter/emerald to $158 so I decided to try the 8.5 again and in this color the fit was perfect. I was able to get my index finger into the back of the boot with my foot pushed forward touching the front, with the trekking sock. The brown model must have been erroneously sized. I walked a couple of miles on my treadmill in these boots and there were no hot spots. I hiked 7 miles in NJ with about a 600 ft elevation gain to break them in and the boots were supportive. This weekend (9/5) I hiked the Pyngyp Circular ln Harriman/Bear Mt, 12 miles and 2000' elevation gain (moderate to strenuous).The trail was dry, very rocky with lots of tree roots and the boots held up well offering good support in a very light weight and comfortable boot. The rubber soles gripped the rocks well scrambling up Pyngyp Mt.

This summer I've fallen in love with Sbicca. I love that the're handmade in the US, and they're super cute.

I work in administration at a botanical garden and needed a pair of sandals that could work with a dress, shorts or jeans, and these fit the bill perfectly. They're comfortable enough that I can wear them giving tours of the grounds, but are dressy enough to work for events as well.

I bought these to replace another pair of Sbicca sandals that I'd worn out. The other pair (slightly different style) was a bit too big, so I got a smaller size for these, and they're kind of snug, but I'm hoping the straps will stretch out just a bit like the last pair did.

Super cute sandals, and if these last as long as my last pair of Sbiccas, I'll certaily be back for more!

column6: Mizuno Men's Wave Inspire 11 Running Shoe
column14: I've owned the 9's, 10's and now the 11's. The 9's were great, went 250 miles or so without any problems. When they wore out, I got a pair of the 10's, expecting the same results. Not even close... They were less durable, slightly less comfortable, the upper material didn't breathe as well and my feet stunk horribly after using them, the tongue was too short and kept falling below the knot during longer runs, and most strangely, my three smallest toes on my left foot were falling asleep during faster training sessions. None of these problems were present with the 9's.. When my 10's wore out after a disappointing 3 months (or maybe I wasn't that disappointed), I began looking at other brands because of the letdown I experienced. I read on a review for a different shoe the greatness of the 11's, and thought it best I give Mizuno another shot. The support, rigidity, fit, and balance I felt with the 9's was a euphoria I wasn't going to give up looking for so easily. THANK GOD Mizuno went back to the proven styling and design of the 9. After a couple runs, my toes aren't going numb, my legs feel energetic after training, and I cut the mysterious time I had gained on my miles without changing anything but my shoes. My feet were so happy to have these, that even a 3 mile night run after getting home from camping for the weekend was a pleasure. I honestly can't wait to get home and pop these beautiful puppies on and go try to work on some PR's!

column6: Sanita Women's Cabrio Clog
column14: First off a general rule of Sanita is to know your European size. It should be noted sometimes 41 is listed as 10, sometimes 10.5-11. It matters not, it's 41. The second thing is if you are used to Dansko, Sanita does run narrower for the B(M) size. If you are used to the width with Dansko, you are probably looking for the wider size, which is the C/D. I personally found the B(M) to fit perfectly. I fit in both sizes, but the C/D is more like the Dansko fit. That being said, I prefer the B(M) size for my feet in Sanita.  These shoes are very well made, and extremely balanced compared to other clogs I have worn, and the arch support is actually better. In terms of colorways, I have found what is out there with Sanita can be very fun.  I am going to have a very hard time justifying buying another pair of Dansko's with the better made and better fitting (for me) Sanita out there.
