column14:
Buyers, beware!!!! These are FAKE Pediped shoes!!! Majority of the shoes that I buy for my daughters are from Pediped, so I know their standard quality very well. Shoes that I received today are so poorly made that it took me two seconds to realize that they were FAKE!

1. Where it says "Arch support" on the insole, there is no padding at all. Insole is absolutely flat!
2. Insole is NOT detachable. It's sewed in like a lining.
3. This is not real leather! Just some kind of cheap material that has strong chemical odor.
4. Stitching is very sloppy.
5. Label was NOT attached! It was just sitting on the bottom of the box.

I'm really disappointed to be ripped off like that! These shoes are going back to their fraudulent seller right away.

column6: adidas Outdoor Men's ClimaCool Boat Pure Running Shoes
column13: The fit on them is like everyone else said
column14:
I bought these to use on a weekend canoe trip. The fit on them is like everyone else said, make sure you get them a whole size smaller. I only went a half size and had to tie them extra tight. When I got these I was looking for something that could be worn all day that the water would drain out of easily and keep my feet cool and dry, and that's exactly what they did. HOWEVER, I want to point out that if you're going to be in any sand whatsoever, these shoes are not a good idea. I ended up going barefoot most of the time unless I really needed shoes, because every time I'd step out of the canoe and into the water, they'd get sand in them. Not a ridiculous amount, but enough that I had to take them off repeatedly to rinse them out. I got plenty of comments about them though. They look like normal tennis shoes.
So, if you're getting them to use in a boat or as a pair of run around shoes, they're perfect, just stay away from the sand. Other than that, they're very comfortable and supportive and incredibly light. Just wearing them to break-in (which was unnecessary, they didn't need it), I kept feeling like I wasn't even wearing shoes. They breathe so well, that the airflow will make you think you've spilled something on you foot. I'd recommend a good pair of laces that stretch, to make them easier to get on and off repeatedly for cleaning.

column13: This thing is just super well made
column14:
[[VIDEOID:bb5686ca76bc755d8c4a6b3fb75cc7fa]] I received a free sample for an evaluation and honest review.

The video shows off the bag and gives my overall impressions of it. Below are some highlights.

First off, this bag is very well made. The whole thing just exudes quality, IMO. Very nice material construction, and not one bit of it feels cheap to me. I also love how the canvas feels - it's just so \\\earthy.\\\\\"

It can hold a decent amount of stuff, but just realize that not all of the pockets are fully contained. There are three zippered pouches about the size of a cell phone that completely close and will hold in your stuff. The front flap does not securely close, so stuff in that front pouch could spill out. Also, the main compartment doesn't completely close - the zipper has opening on both ends. While any large object in the main compartment will be contained easily, small items could fall out.

As long as you're okay with it not completely securely everything, I have no problem recommending this. The quality construction and great feel of the material are fantastic. This is one of the products that I knew as I unpacked it that it was very well made. Some things come across as cheap, but not this. Every detail is well made, but just know that not every pocket is completely secure."

column6: Lodis Audrey Liat Tote
column14:
First impressions ... the color is darker than I expected and represented by the picture. That aside it is an absolutely stunning bag. The leather is stiff and smooth to the touch, and so constructed that it stands upright. The stitching is neat and precise and in a contrasting beige. The edges are a pale pink / orange . There is an open pocket in front with a teeny "Lodis" logo that is almost inconspicuous. The interior is a chevron patterned, logo white and grey material, with one zippered pocket in the rear panel and two open pockets in the center panel. The shoulder straps fits comfortably over my shoulders and it came with a logo dust bag.

My overall impression is that this is a well structured tote, and now that I see it it is too good for the purpose that I intended (i.e. airport diaper / tote bag). It is also nice and large, length and breath wise, but not width. Well done Lodis, you just made a customer for life.

column13: Hoping this was just a lemon
column14:
My first pair was a gift in this same style when it was called ‚ÄúYolanda,‚Äù way before Vionic technology was even added to them. Since then, I have been buying Orthoheel for years and this is the first time I have been disappointed by them. Four months of moderate wear and sides have pulled away from the main base and the toe post has ripped, exposing the strings.
On a positive note, this style is amazing for people with width issues. It fits true to size because of the ability to adjust in the straps and the arch technology really makes a difference in everyday life. I used to have an issue with one of my feet swelling due to poor circulation. These honestly have helped and I haven't had issues since I started using them.
I'm hoping this issue with qualify is not the new normal. I will try them again and see if maybe I just received a lemon this time around.

column6: Vivobarefoot Men's Sofa RA II Lace-Up Shoes
column14:
I had the original Vivobarefoot Ra's, and I loved them. They had a couple fit issues though, mostly in that they were too wide for me. The Vivobarefoot shoes are supposed to be wide so that your foot can spread out, but the original Ras were really really wide. The newer ones are a tad narrower, so if you were really happy with the originals, you won't be so happy with the Ra IIs.

Overall, the Ra IIs are just okay. The build quality of these (might just be the SofA ones) is not very good. The insole has wrinkles in it and the outsole has already seperated from the upper. Its held on by the stiching, so its not gaping off, but that shouldn't happen in the short time that I've owned them (about 2 weeks). The heel is also constructed funny, I think it might be a design issue though. It slants really severely to the front of the shoe as it comes up from the sole, so it really digs into my heel. I've taken scissors and trimmed the seam, maybe that'll allow the heel to stretch a bit more. Or maybe I just ruined my shoes and made it so I can't return them.

column6: Keen Women's Newport H2
column13: So much more comfortable than I anticipated
column14:
I needed a pair of shoes to wear on a lazy river tubing event, and the reviews I read said these would be good for that purpose. They were great. I was able to navigate on slippery river rocks with no problems. They were muddy and dirty when I got home so I threw them in the washing machine and they looked brand new after the wash.

This was my first pair of Keen shoes and they were so much more comfortable than I anticipated they would be. I am somewhat of a comfort shoe snob - I love Birkenstock, Finn, Dansko, Naot, Mephisto and Ecco, so I know good shoes. These rank right up there with my other favorite brands. The arch is not as pronounced as with Finn and Dansko, but for a day of water activities, I would not want such a high arch anyway. I have very sensitive feet and am prone to blisters, so I'm always cautious when wearing a new pair. Even though I brought a 2nd pair in case these started to rub my sensitive skin, I did not need them. I wore these Keen shoes all day with no problems. I highly recommend them.

column13: What really amazes me is that after coming up with near perfect model of K-Swiss Men's Ultrascendor
column14: They managed to screw up this one up. Too narrow in the midfoot and toe box, too wide in the ankle. Effect is slipping of the foot in the ankle when you lean forward (despite rougher inside at the back of the shoe which will probably rip your socks). Also, because of tighter and more narrow mid section, this shoe will be prone to foot roll. What really amazes me is that after coming up with near perfect model of K-Swiss Men's Ultrascendor, they steadily has been keep going down. First, they replaced natural leather with plastic that cracks after few months, squeaks and does not breath. For what? To lower the price from 100 to 75? I have tons of options below 70 for cheap, plastic crap. Maybe because it is just hard for them to get real leather, who knows. My advise to you guys is go back to your original, natural leather K-Swiss Men's Ultrascendor Shoe. Please, do it quick before you lose most of your customers. I am already one foot out testing other brands...

column14: Great at first but poor quality for what you pay.  This was exactly what I was looking for (plain solid color thick flip flop with a comfortable cloth thong) but the price is a little high for what you get.  I was trying to find a match for a great sandal I found at Walmart several years ago.  You can see in the picture that this is made out of several layers of foam.  The top layer is squishy and comfortable but the bottom ones are much harder so they're not as comfortable as they could be.  This also caused the part where the cloth top meets the sides to rip the foam on the sides and release the cloth part, breaking the shoe.  I think I've had these maybe 3 months and one is already broken (gentle use too, just walking a little bit each day). column6: FRYE Women's Phillip Seam Ankle Dress Sandal
column13: Frye! Why would you stop making the most gorgeous, comfortable sandal of all time and replace it with this?
column14:
I already have the (different) Frye Phillip 2 Piece Sandal, and it is the most comfortable sandal I have ever put on my feet. I would buy a pair in every color if I could find them. Since Frye (inexplicably) stopped making those, I thought I'd try this one, the Phillip Seam Ankle. They are NOT the same thing. In my usual size 9 (the same size I take in non-Frye shoes, but larger than the 8 1/2 I take in Frye closed toe shoes/boots), the foot bed and toe fit the same way as the Phillip 2 Piece, but the ankle strap (which is a design difference between the them) does not work for me. I have thin, boney ankles, and the super short straps barely extended around them. To make matters worse, the back strap that comprises the heel of the sandal and attaches to the ankle strap cut into my foot/ankle in several places. Ouch.
Frye! Why would you stop making the most gorgeous, comfortable sandal of all time and replace it with this?
Please bring back the Phillip 2 Piece Sandal!!!!

column6: Womens Small Leather Wallet Card Case Change Purse Button Snap Closed
column13: it's easy to start lugging a lot of junk around with ...
column14:
Let me start by saying I wanted a tiny wallet to go with my tiny fossil purse because I'm trying to simplify -- when you carry a giant handbag, it's easy to start lugging a lot of junk around with you!
So, be prepared to make sacrifices with this wallet. I have 5 cards, then cash. And that's all!
There's the ID window, two slots on inner front part where it snaps closed, then an interior pocket and tiny zippered section, then a final pocket/card slot on the back. In the interior pocket, there are two things I wish I could remove -- 1) the manufacturer tag and 2) an attached key ring. However, the space is too snug to get down there and remove those items. So I flipped the attached key ring over the side and out -- I use it as the thing I grab when pulling my wallet out of my purse, and the tag just gets smushed down there and keeps my cash from cooperating and sitting down in the wallet.
And the ID window is tiny (it couldn't really be made any larger though) so be prepared to just take your ID out if you're young-looking and going out to the bar.

column6: FRYE Women's Paige Tall Riding Boot
column13: People with high insteps, do not despair!
column14:
I own these boots in the gorgeous whiskey color. I have a high instep, so my first day with them, we were not friends. However, I was determined not to let the boots win. These are the best quality boots I have ever owned (or shoes for that matter) so I wasn't quite prepared for how the leather would behave. I read a million reviews about how boots with no zipper were a struggle to put on, especially for those of us with high insteps and arches. Try as I might (and I tried to the point of working up a sweat), I could not get my heels past the ankle portion of the boot. Knowing this was a common problem, I held out hope.

Today, determined to wear these beautiful boots that I had waited years to own, I tried again. Plastic grocery bags over my stocking feet did the trick! It took about twenty minutes (ten per boot) to get them on by pushing each foot firmly against the wall, tugging at the pull tabs, and easing my toes forward, but once my heel worked its way past the ankle, it slid right in.

These boots, once on, are exceptionally comfortable. They seem to fit true to size. I know it will take a few more wears for my feet to fully conform to the leather, but I'm confident they will fit like a glove once fall rolls around. These are definitely worth the investment, both in price and time!

column13: Exactly what I wanted - perfect style, fit, comfort, and price point.
column14: I love these. I needed some sort of casual, oxford-esque sneaker as a daily running-around, matches-everything shoe. These are comfy right from the get go, fit snugly on my narrow heel but have adequate space for my toes (I usually need a much wider/more forgiving toe box in most shoes). Would easily fit someone with smaller feet, too. I usually wear an 8.5-9 for most shoes, which almost always means a 9 for Sanuk (any style). A little tight to first slip on but definitely feel like the soft fabric will break in easily, and I'm not experiencing any chafing. Good with or without socks, like most Sanuk's. The sole doesn't have arch support (it isn't supposed to - think ballet flats or flip flops!) and is very soft and comfortable. These will be a great alternative to casual flats and I can even ride my bike while wearing them. Besides which, they are super cute! The details are very subtle but give this shoe some personality. column6: Island Surf Men's Mako 3-strap Sandals
column14:
Very light and comfortable. Flex well with movement without the irritation that nylon straps give. The soles are about as simple and light as you can find. Footbed is easily cleaned and breaths extremely well. This are a good middle ground between the comfort of pure padded leather with its tendency to get nasty from perspiration, and the clean feel of rubber/nylon sandals with their limited comfort and wearability. Also were great on the Arkansas River rafting trip we did last week. If we could get the same comfort as padded leather on the uppers, they would be a five-star plus.

They have become my go-to sandals, wearing them daily rather than my Ch***os or padded leathers.

column6: ECCO Men's Fusion Slip-On Loafer
column13: The most comfortable shoes I own.
column14:
I have several pairs of these shoes (two in brown, and one in black), and I absolutely love them. They fit ridiculously comfortably.

For me, personally, when I try on a pair of shoes - they have to fit comfortably immediately. I've been told far too many times when I've found a shoe initially uncomfortable that, "You need to wear them in a little and they'll get more comfortable." No, I say. Just... no. I can't think of a single time where this is true. If a shoe is not comfortable out of the box, I'm not going to wear it because it never gets more comfy.

So, with these ECCO Fusion Slip-Ons, I'm thrilled to find they always fit like a cozy glove every time I get a new pair.

They hold up really well, look really smart, provide great arch support, and I can walk for hours in them. Highly recommended.

5 stars out of 5.

column6: Patagonia Men's EVERlong Trail Running Shoe
column13: Great shoe with a peculiar feature.
column14:
These shoes are truly great with the exception of one thing, and that is the pointed toe. I've accumulated about 100 miles on these since getting them the other month and I really find the time I spend in them to be enjoyable and comfortable. Add to the fact that when I purchased them they were $45 and you've got a very happy customer.

The cushioning on these is very nice, it's plush but not a pillow and you still get good ground feel. The shoes are extremely flexible and light which is important to me. However, as I stated in my opening sentence, the shoes have a pointed toe like a road shoe. I'm not sure why they did this, but I constantly catch my toes on roots and rocks when wearing these and today even managed to trip myself. These are still my go to summer time trail shoe, but the pointed toe certainly brings down some of the fun when trying to rip through the woods.

column13: Just as good, if not better than Converse!
column14: I ordered these to go along with a genderbent cosplay I am planning, and they look durable enough to wear for everyday use! The shoes fit exactly as my normal Converse brand shoes do, which was great because then I didn't have to return them, and the material they are made out of feels exactly the same as brand-name Converse shoes. They arrived 2 days earlier than the ETA for free standard shipping, which was awesome. I had read reviews on these shoes that the laces would be too short to lace them up every single hole, so lacing them every other hole would be advised. However, when I tried this, the laces ended up being too long and the ends were uneven with each other. If you unlace them down to where it's straight across at the bottom of the lacing and align the ends, they should be long enough to lace all the way up to the top, though the bow might be small depending on how tight you lace them. The zipper on the side works perfectly, it wasn't coming off like I had seen in other reviews, and the only issue i had with them was trying to zip them while wearing jeans, as the leg of my jeans kept getting caught in them. All-in-all, these shoes are just as good as name-brand Converses, good for the price (considering converses run about $50-$60), and they're tall, which is good since in my state, they discontinued selling the tall Converses.

column6: AmeriBag Esopus Shoulder Bag
column13: Don't Be Fooled By Its Size!
column14:
I was shopping for a new AmeriBag Healthy Back bag in black microfiber. I saw this little bag, also by AmeriBag, looked at the measurements and assumed they were a typo. I ordered anyhow, because as much as I love AmeriBag's Healthy Back bag it doesn't go with every outfit. Besides, I could return it. Right? When this bag arrived I was peeved to discover the listed measurements were pretty much correct. A little girl's purse?

But, oh, my ... I love it! Look at the picture of the bag while I take you on a tour ...

First unzip the flap. We will get to the bottom zipper later. With the flap open, right away you see it is not a child's toy. The inside of the bag has AmeriBag's signature silver lining so you can see everything in it.

The open flap has a side-entry translucent pocket where you may put your driver's license and possibly a credit card right behind it. Below, at the bottom of the inside of the flap is a mesh pocket, the width of the flap, with a zipper. A good place to put money -- bills and change. Looking now at the whole bag on the inside I notice that there is an attached key fob, as well as many storage pockets of varying shapes and sizes. There are two open pockets on the back of the inside of the bag. Running across the front of those pockets are two wide strips of elastic, strong enough to hold just about anything in place. On either side of the inside of the bag there are two cone-shaped pockets -- one of mesh, the other of the same silver lining. Oh, wait -- turn the bag around and look inside of the front of the bag near the bottom. Another zippered pocket! There also is space in the middle of the bag for my cell phone (Blackberry Z10).

A heavy grosgrain covers the otherwise raw edges of all the fabrics -- mesh, silver lining and microfiber. The outside zippered pocket, on the front of the bag near the bottom might be perfect for a small pair of reading glasses. It also has a very long,but adjustable, detachable microfiber shoulder strap and a fixed handle, also of microfiber, on the top of the flap where it becomes the top of the bag when the flap is zipped closed

The only place that the workmanship is a little sloppy is where the two pockets are stitched to the inside back of the bag.

I wish ... the shoulder strap had something on it to keep the bag from slipping off my shoulder ... there was a hook-and-loop fastener to keep the open edge of the translucent pocket closed. Otherwise, practically perfect!

It is unlikely that this cute little bag will become an everyday bag for me -- but who knows? It certainly carries just about everything I need. This bag is the "Tiny House" of bags. I hope you love it, too!

column6: Teva Women's Hurricane XLT Sandal, Hazel Black, 9 US
column14:
I am constantly searching for comfortable shoes, but often find myself disappointed with what's available. These Tevas are the exception! They're super comfortable and can be worn all day in a variety of terrains. I primarily use them while camping and kayaking, and they easily go from trail to lake and back again. The tread on these shoes is great, and although I'm normally incredibly clumsy and unsteady on my feet, I've never had traction issues while wearing these.

Alll that being said, I do think this shoe runs a bit big. I usually wear a 7, but could probably stand to size down in this shoe for a better fit. My feet are also on the average-wide side, and I find these shoes to fit perfectly, which means they may be a bit wide to some people.

column6: Under Armour Prevail Sunglasses
column14: It took me a while to get accustomed to the larger size of these glasses, but for a larger person (6'4), they fit and look perfectly fine (If you are a smaller framed person, these might look like one of those sunglasses/sunshields that go over normal prescription glasses lol). The grey lenses are a perfect shade that are not too dark but not too light. They will be plenty fine for those bright days on the lake and light enough for a mostly cloudy day. I have sensitive eyes so even a cloudy day can seem pretty bright to me. They definitely have that cool factor and it is hard to see the wearer's eyes through the lens'. They also fit my croakies so I can wear them around my neck. For 45 bucks, this is a great deal for a great looking/performing pair of shades.

column6: Coleman Women's CC1 6024 Polarized Sunglasses Audrey Hepburn Style
column13: A Definite Must Have!  Perfect Sunglasses!!
column14:
I have been wearing the same pair of polarized glasses for about 15 years, which retailed for over $100. There is some wear on the lens and I really needed to find a good replacement for them. I have searched for a few pair and could never find any that I like. These look similar to the ones that I have, so I thought that I would try them out. After being given a discounted rate in exchange for my honest review, I was hoping for something that I could use daily and for a good long time. I just got these about an hour ago and I am extremely pleased with them already.

First, these come in their own little drawstring bag, for their protection. They are so amazing looking, I couldn't wait to try them on. As soon as I did, I knew that I had found my replacement. They are a perfect fit on my face, to the point that I cannot even tell that I have them on. That is how lightweight that these glasses are. Even my husband complimented me on them.

These are beautifully made. They have a silver band with little accents on each stem of the glasses. The frame is perfectly made and the lenses are truly the best part. If you have never owned a pair of polarized lenses, they are a must have. I have a sensitivity to light and these are truly the best thing to wear to cut down on any glare from other cars, the sun, anything that just flashes in your eyes while driving, walking, jogging. Plus, they block 100% UV. In this day, that is a great feature.

Extremely pleased with these glasses and would recommend them to any one that goes outside for anything!

column6: Clarks Men's Wave.Post Slip-On
column13: Comfortable - Breathable - Leather Shoe - Well Done Clarks
column14: I love these shoes.  They are light-weight and very breathable. I'm super picky when it comes to one thing and that's comfort.  I'm a moderate overpronator and an avid somewhat overweight tennis player.  Needless to say my feet take a beating.  They crave cushioning particularly in the forefoot and stability through the arch/mid-foot and heel. These shoes provide the cushioning and stability without feeling squishy(like memory foam) or stiff.  My feet are a bit wide but not E width wide and these fit perfectly.  A word of warning, if you've never tried a wave line shoe they will feel odd the first time.  I wore the first pair I tried on around a store for 30 minutes to make sure I could get used to the feeling.  After wearing them to work everyday for two weeks, I ordered another pair.  Nothing worse than your new favorite shoes becoming extinct before you wear the first pair out.

XX2i is committed to producing the best possible eyewear for outdoor enthusiasts and stand behind each product they produce with integrity and pride. They want to insure that you are completely satisfied, no matter what. XX2i sunglasses are not available in stores from what I could find, but they offer the best warranty that I have seen, anywhere. You can try them for 365 days and if you don‚Äôt like them, you can return them and get your money back. Also, they have a ‚Äúno questions asked‚Äù lifetime warranty, even if you scratch or break the glasses.

I was very pleased with the France 2 sunglasses when I reviewed them on my blog in June (click here for the review). They were a great pair of shades for a great price. I got an email from the rep at XX2i about testing out the USA1 and was excited to test them out as well.

Again, the USA 1 sunglasses start at $59.99, but you could choose to purchase sets with additional lenses for $99.99. They showed up with a hard case, soft microfiber bag, and a sunglass cord. The hard case had spots for the sunglasses and separate spots for the lenses as well. It is the same case setup that came with the France 2, which is one of the best cases that I have received to date.

They wanted to send me the Crystal Clear sunglasses with green temple tips and the Flash Green lenses. While some people (including my wife) might not care for the color scheme, I really liked it. If that color scheme doesn‚Äôt work for you, they have other colors to choose from. The USA 1 has anti-fog cutouts, which the France 2 did not have.

XX2i Optics calls their lenses 4k ultra high definition, a marketing term that refers to Advanced Chromatic Filtering, High Scratch Resistance, Impact Resilience, and Lifetime Warranty. The lenses were great; clear and did not distort anything. You can get polarized lenses as well.

Pros:
Very light weight material
Great Value (Starting at $59.99)
Great fit, doesn‚Äôt move around or bounce while running
Unbeatable warranty

Cons:
Not available in stores

The France 2 sunglasses fit really well, but the USA 1 fit even better. These are a premium sunglass without the premium price. They only cost $59.99, fit great, and have the best warranty in the business. It doesn‚Äôt get any better than that. Grab a pair today!

To the person complaining about how these 60's style glasses aren't of the same quality as the ones he bought in the 60's and are more expensive than the ones he bought in the 60's: seriously d00d that was 50 years ago and thanks to the progress of science and industry we developed these cool space-age materials in the decades since, such as plastics and lightweight amorphous metals that are far more durable than the brittle nylon and tin alloys used back then. As for price there is this thing called "inflation" (maybe you've heard of it?). Just like gas (petrol) today costs many times more than the $0.05/gallon that it did back in the 60's, these shades would be the equivalent of $2.50 pair of shades from the 60's which is priced just about right. column6: Deception IV: The Nightmare Princess - PlayStation 4
column14:
Deception IV: The Nightmare Princess is a great touch-up on the Deception IV: Blood Ties game. For those who have already had a chance to play the game, this version does not offer a ton of new content, though the additional story and quests certainly provide some fun. If you are new to the game or series and want something unique to play? This game is devilish fun and easy to recommend.

The Deception series has always been a difficult one to define. I fell in love with the first game on the original PlayStation, when it was called Tecmo's Deception: An Invitation to Darkness. That is quite the title, but it was also quite the game as Deception left a huge impression on me. The game was dark, brooding and had a completely unique feeling to it. This is true of the narrative, but also the gameplay which had elements of action, RPGs and strategy laced throughout the gameplay.

Fast forward to now with Deception IV: The Nightmare Princess and we have a game that embraces many of these same principles as you take the role of Laegrinna - a 'daughter' of the Devil made up of a fragment of his soul. This was part of the original Deception IV title, but now a new character named Velguirie has been introduced with a more mission-oriented sort of approach to the story. Both characters are similar in that they do not directly defend themselves, but instead use traps around their environment to do their dirty work.

I have always felt like the early Deception game laid down some of the framework for titles like Dungeon Defenders and Orcs Must Die! These are titles that are tower defense with a more personal touch because of the character you control on the battlefield. In Deception it is not so much tower defense as using your own character as the bait that your enemies are making their way towards. They want to kill you for a variety of reasons. Some are mercenaries or knights who are hunting you down either for money or righteousness, while others have simply happened upon your location through ill fortune.

The idea is basically the same at that point. Use traps to damage, kill or capture the intruders. There are traps that you can set, and you choose from a variety of them to be equipped with before each level. These can range from ground-based beartraps and explosions to wall mounted spikes and fireballs to raining death from above in the form of boulders and pumpkins. Yes, pumpkins - but it makes sense in a moment. There are also traps built into the environment, such as using a swinging axe trap to knock a column down onto a trapped intruder, or catapulting a hapless victim into the belly of a giant flaming bronze bull.

Each trap comes in one of three flavors. You have Elaborate, Sadistic and Humiliating. Elaborate tend to be more about impacting a character's movements. These tend to involve beartraps, suction walls and walls that can push people into other spaces. They deal damage, but are usually more useful in getting someone lined up for bigger combinations and hits. Sadistic generally deals heavy damage, such as a swinging axe from the ceiling or triggering a statue holding a great sword to swing its arm down and strike an intruder. Humiliating are usually the least likely to be avoided, but also do not necessarily do a great deal of damage. They can be useful or lining someone up for a combination, but they tend to be a bit more difficult to predict as well. Drop a pumpkin on someone's head, and they will march off in a specific direction for a time, but it is the direction they are already facing. If they turn at the last moment, it could mess up your entire combination.

Of course, enemies are not always going to simply walk right where you want them to. Some use jumping attacks to get close, while others use magic or arrows for ranged attacks. Some are certainly foolish, but these tend to deal the most damage if they get within range. Considering you often are competing with two or three enemies at a time, and it can be tough to focus on just one person while running from one location to the other. I will say that this game is much harder than the original deception - I used to just make use of narrow hallways and beat people to death with spikes in the walls. The game has come a long ways since then.

The pace of Nightmare Princess might not suit everyone. There is a lot of waiting to lure people where you want them, and while I find the payoff to be exceedingly satisfying when it works, it can also be very frustrating when it fails. Add to that the somewhat squishy nature of the primary characters, and later levels will likely kill you a great deal. Replaying the same three or four guys to get back to the wave that did you in can be a fifteen to thirty minute experience that I am certainly willing to live with give the game's devilish charms, but if you are looking for fast-paced action, Deception might not be the series for you.

Combining specific types of combinations, meeting the requests of your three helpers (essentially optional quests that yield more experience and money) and purchasing new traps and powers all serve as excellent progression hooks that kept me coming back for me. While this is a single player game, there are some options for creating scenarios and uploading and downloading them. The same is true of replay videos. These tools help to add to the title's replay value and they kept me coming back for more.

Deception IV: The Nightmare Princess is the best version of the game by far. I had a chance to play Blood Ties on both the Vita and the PlayStation 3 initially, and it is a better experience here. The additional content is a nice touch, and while the visuals do not press the PlayStation 4 hardware, load times are actually quite snappy and help to take some of the sting out of dying and having to reload again. The end result is a deviously entertaining strategy game with RPG and action elements that allows you to embrace being the villain in a fun way.ompeting with two or three enemies at a time, and it can be tough to focus on just one person while running from one location to the other. column6: Sony PlayStation 4 PS4 Dualshock 4 Wireless Control
column13: 3rd controller in less than a year.
column14:
Sony really dropped the ball when they made these. Of course the design in classic, but the build quality is atrocious. In a lifetime of gaming I have never come across so a fragile controller.
The rubber on the thumbsticks runs out quickly, which isn't a huge problem and has allegedly been fixed on newer versions. The springs on the triggers fail completely. The wire which connects the touch pad is held in by nothing more than faith - this is really unbelievable and has to be seen to really be believed. Let's not forget the unchangeable battery life is laughable. All these problems and more can be yours for the low price of $60.
I recently had to open my Xbox One controller and was shocked by how much better the thing is built, it's a tank by comparison.

Sony will repair the controller for free within a year of purchase, just pay to ship it back. However unless you can be without a controller for up to a few weeks you'll still need to buy a new one.

Sadly the 3rd party options are all worse and it,s this or nothing. At least while it lasts it feels good in your hand.

column6: Wolfenstein: The New Order
column14:
This review has troubled me more than most as I‚Äôm still trying to decide exactly how I feel about WOLFENSTEIN: THE NEW ORDER. There‚Äôs much to like here. Visually, the game is impressive, the combat is fun and quite challenging on the higher difficulties, and the story, although a little cheesy, and not a match for such franchises as BioShock or Half-Life, is pretty good. And the voice acting is solid throughout. There are also some impressive cut-scenes and very enjoyable set-pieces. Despite all this, however, the overall lasting impression of the game is that it somehow falls a little flat. Perhaps it‚Äôs the fact that there are so many cutscenes where control is suddenly wrenched away from the player (I like a good cutscene as much as the next gamer and they are necessary to flesh-out a full story, but here there are so many of them it sometimes disturbs the rhythm of the game). Or maybe it‚Äôs the rail-like, linear nature of the game and the lack of variety in the environments. Or it might be the fact that, although the game tries to offer a mix of stealth and run-and-gun it really only gets the latter right. Or maybe it‚Äôs just me. It‚Äôs true to say the same can be said about many good games and it would be unfair to criticise WTNO too much for having these traits. But at the end of the day, although I enjoyed WTNO, and will stick with the franchise, I‚Äôm left with mixed feelings about the overall experience. Oh, and it‚Äôs yet another game with no quick save, which is annoying.
3.5/5

column6: Tearaway
column13: Tearaway is one of my favorite games that I ever played
column14:
From the minds behind LittleBigPlanet and LittleBigPlanet 2 comes the 3D platformer, Tearaway. Honestly, Tearaway is one of my favorite games that I ever played. I kind just spoiled the review a little, though I couldn't help it. Tearaway is just full of creativity, humor, and the most important factor of them all, fun.

The story stars the messengers, Iota or Atoi (Depending if you choose male or female.), and the You. The You is well you. As the You, your goal to help the messengers deliver a message to you. The game places you into the game using the front facing camera to put your face into the sun or whenever you use the back-touch pad your finger comes out from the ground. Being in the narrative doesn't cause any weird disconnect as Tearaway‚Äôs world and yours interact. It works really well and makes the ending a really touching experience with a great message.

Tearaway controls like a everyday 3D platformer, though due to the PS Vita having some unique functions that other consoles don't have it takes a very unique twist with how you play. Every single feature that there is on the PS Vita, Tearaway uses it and they all work wonderfully. Using the touch screen to interact with platforms and poking nasty enemies called Scraps, using the back-touch pad in certain areas allows your finger to tear through the floor to interact with objects or platforms, and for some quests you take real world pictures with rear facing camera for various applications. For example, there is an elk that had lost her color in her fur. She requested me to find her a more vibrant fur. I took a picture of grass in my backyard and the grassy texture covered the elk.

Tearaway has some of the best graphics I have seen in a video game. Tearaway‚Äôs levels are entirely made from sheets of paper. The levels are beautifully designed and each piece of paper seems to be an animated object of it's own. It makes the locations look vibrant, dynamic, and just fun to play through.
Within the environments there are secrets and unlockables hidden behind tabs of paper that you'd pull with your finger or using the positioning of the camera to cleverly hide these secrets. The secrets consist pieces of confetti, presents, and certain objects in the environments that you have opportunity to take photos of with the in-game camera your messenger receives.

The unlockables are very unique in Tearaway. With the confetti you can buy paper parts to completely customize the messengers. You can purchase eyes, mouths, and other accessories. Players are also able to draw their own accessories using sheets of paper of various colors with the touchscreen. There is really no limit what you can do and all of these customizations carry over into the cutscenes which is awesome.

I mentioned about the opportunities to take photos of certain objects in the environments with the in-game camera. When you take pictures of these certain objects you unlock directions on how to make paper-crafts out of these objects out in the real world. Which is a very neat and fun way to do unlockables within a video game.

Everything just works so well together in Tearaway. The soundtrack is really good, unique, super catchy and it fits with the game's paper crafted world well. All of the PS Vita's features work well to make Tearaway an interesting and fun experience for all ages. Tearaway is one of my favorite games for the PS Vita and even one of my favorite games of all time. Tearaway is a well crafted classic that is a must buy for every PS Vita and a game that can not be played on any other console.lay through.

column6: LEGO Jurassic Parent
column14:
Dinosaurs. LEGOs. Those two things alone should spark the imagination of almost any kid - I certainly recall them coming together frequently in my childhood, and they seem like a perfect pairing for a video game as well. That the recent Jurassic World movie was such a huge success should only reinforce the likelihood that the game is well-received. The good news is, the video game holds up quite well as a creative, kid-friendly take on the movie.

If there was a complaint from critics about the Jurassic World movie, it was some nitpicking over some of the finer points in the storyline. This did not seem to bother audience goers much as they flocked to see it in theaters and seemed to enjoy it. LEGO Jurassic World should appeal on a similar front. You do not get lost in any sort of story minutia here, but you do get to relive many of the bigger scenes from the movie, all against a background of bricks and amusing characters.

Like the LEGO Hobbit game, this one actually pulls from story lines found in Jurassic Park, The Lost World and Park III as well as Jurassic World. This gives gamers a plethora of content to work through, with lots of brick-based environments to sort through, plenty of characters to play and of course, lots of adorably cute dinosaurs that make up the high points in the game.

One of the best design choices in this game is the ability to let players take control of the dinosaurs and wreck havoc with them. The dinosaurs plod about in somewhat difficult-to-control fashion at times, but they are still a great deal of fun. This was a great decision because the human characters really lack for variation. This is not like a Hobbit game where you might have dwarves, archers and magic users that have different skills, or the Marvel game where the superheroes have lots of unique abilities. Certainly some humans in this can do specific things better than others, but it was a smart design choice to allow for non-human characters to control.

As always, there is a sort of LEGO brand of humor at play here that works so well with the bricks and the story content. I remember being impressed years ago when I first played the Star Wars titles in LEGO form - I came away thoroughly impressed with how expressive the silent characters could be, and how funny the end results were. Fast forward to where the LEGO games are at now, and the characters are far more expressive than ever and this allows that trademark humor to really shine.

Of course there are a ton of unlockables as you play, which gives the game a good deal of replay value. This is not the longest of games - each of the four chapters takes a little less than two hours to complete, so you are only spending about seven or eight hours on the entirety of the campaign. The unclockable content gives you a great excuse to go back and try some of your favorite levels again. The desire to do so is helped by great level design, charming visuals and a sound track that really soars when it needs to. To me LEGO has always been synonymous with imagination, and this is a game where it is easy for the imagination to get swept away in the fun.

There are a few bugs here and there, and I do wish the dinosaurs controlled a bit better at times, but all in all LEGO Jurassic World is arguably the best installment in the LEGO series in the last couple of years. It will appeal to a large audience, it gives you a lot to do and... oh yeah, there are dinosaurs. My inner child absolutely approves of that.to control.

column6: Mega Man Anniversary Collection - PlayStation 2
column13: This is the definitive version of Mega Man 1 through 8 and is even better than the new Legacy Collection.
column14:
The PlayStation 2 is well-known for having some of the best collections on it and this one is definitely one of the best. The Mega Man Anniversary Collection comes with Mega Man, Mega Man 2, Mega Man 3, Mega Man 4, Mega Man 5, Mega Man 6, Mega Man 7, Mega Man 8, Mega Man: The Power Battles, and Mega Man 2: The Power Fighters.

All of which are presented with their original graphics as well as new options which you can turn on or off such as added difficulty settings, an option to use the original 8-bit soundtrack or a remixed CD quality soundtrack (which was previously used in the Japan-exclusive "Rockman: Complete Works" and sound really nice, a weapon switch button which was later used in Mega Man 9 & 10, and a save feature! No longer do you need to write down passwords as the game will save your current game progress to your memory card after you complete a stage.

This version also removes all lag from the games, especially noticeable in Mega Man 3 which is infamous for lagging on the NES. The games overall feel much smoother now and refined, even though nothing about them as changed. I do have to warn you though on the GameCube version the jump and shoot buttons are reversed - meaning that A shoots and B jumps. It's not a deal breaker however if you can get this on the PS2 or Xbox I'd suggest it.

The reason I would suggest getting this version over the upcoming Mega Man Legacy Collection on PS4, Xbox One, Steam, and Nintendo 3DS is because that version is more expensive and comes with less features than this one even though this one is a decade older.

OVERALL: I think this is one of the best collections on the market. It has so much content and anyone who is looking to get into Mega Man or relive their childhood should pick up this version because it is truly the definitive version.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Elite 800X Premium Fully Wireless Gaming Headset - DTS Headphone:X 7.1 Surround Sound - Noise Cancellation- Xbox One, Mobile Devices
column13: What were you thinking Turtle Beach?
column14:
I have always liked Turtle Beach headsets. They are hands down some of the best headsets on the market for console gamers. I have owned many headsets from them and I have always been beyond satisfied with the product. They have always been of very high quality and worked flawlessly with no issues. With that said, I am completely and utterly astounded at how disappointing the 800X turned out. I feel like Turtle Beach has done a complete 180 with this product and forgot that they were designing it for the Xbox. Yes the sound quality from the headphones are great, they are super comfy, and you don't have to worry about wires going to your controller or those crappy mic adapters, but unfortunately these are a complete flop for use as a gaming headset. First of all, hidden mics are terrible! Why on earth would you not put a boom mic on an Xbox headset? While I was playing online my party members would constantly tell me to speak up. I had the mic set to the quiet room mode and I still had to shout in order for anyone to hear me clearly. Additionally, the mic monitoring is also pretty bad and it sounds like I'm speaking into a tin can. Both are far cries from my old Earforce Seven Pro and even my X12. The other issue I have been having is that every time I put the headset on charge I have to do a hard reset when playing the next time because the headset won't turn on. It turns on just fine when its not put on the cradle but for some reason putting it on the cradle completely messes everything up. Now I'm a pretty tech savvy guy, so naturally rather then returning these right away or complaining about them I looked up my issues in google and sure enough there's a software patch that fixes these issues. But guess what? Turtle Beach disabled the firmware update before I purchased this $300 paperweight! They took it down 7/17/15 and as I write this review (8/3/15) the firmware update is still unavailable. I'm very disappointed with you Turtle Beach. I'm not waiting any longerand I have already put in my return request.

TL;DR - Headphones sound good, super comfy, mics suck, frequently freezes, no firmware update. If you're going to buy this check to make sure they put the firmware update back up before doing so!

column6: Tales of Xillia 2
column13: A great sequel but still a little depressing
column14:
Your obsession of Tales games will be well fed with this game. If you loved Xillia 1, you will enjoy the slight differences of gameplay and characters in Xillia 2. The fight system is still flashy, but also different with the new hero's "Chromatus" mode. Ludger also has THREE weapons, and depending on who you link with, you will explore many variations of his linked artes and mystic artes. You will be able to play with all your favorite characters from the first game, now taking on different roles 1 year after the original gameplay. Unfortunately, unless linked with Ludger, we don't get to see any other special linked mystic artes (other than Jude/Milla who are defined as the game's OTP).

The Original Soundtrack is rougher here, as you are now playing a character from Elympios, and Motoi Sakuraba's edgier sounds are well displayed in addition to all the familiar themes from major Rieze Maxian destinations, like Nia Kherra, Hamil and Kanbalar. You have to remember that Elympios is technologically savvy and more cosmopolitan than any place in Rieze Maxia. They've also depleted their spirits so most places are barren deserts outside of the cities so their world limited to a few major destinations. But there are softer tones to the main character Ludger as well, and the "Hymn of Proof" and the story behind it will make you roll into fetal position unless you have no heart. In that case, no worries then.

Each character from Xillia 1 has sidequests in Xillia 2, and as the new guy on the block Ludger learns more about them by traveling with them as they in exchange help him complete his quest to save the world. The game may feel a little "rehashed" from the first, but you definitely get to explore more of Elympios this time and the story behind the two worlds as well as battle new quasi-villains in the tradition of Tales games.

The storyline is kind of a downer and in the end, your choices define both the level of affinity between Ludger and his new friends as well as the ending. There are four endings that I've counted and none of the endings are really all that great. You're forced to choose and the producers wanted you to feel Ludger's choice keenly, whatever it is.

If you're new to the Tales series, you might be missing out on some of the subtle Tales themes, but the characters are all very likable and the battle mode ranges from "easy" to "unknown" and you can switch it anytime you're stumped. If you like JRPGs generally, questing, gathering, and grinding, this will be your cup of tea. After 90+ hours of gameplay and three different endings, I still occasionally go back to the coliseum to bash monsters because I really loved the characters and the Xillia universe.evel of affinity between Ludger and his new friends as well as the ending. There are four endings that I've counted and none of the endings are really all that great. You're forced to choose and the producers wanted you to feel Ludger's choice keenly, whatever it is.

After 90+ hours of gameplay and three different endings, I still occasionally go back to the coliseum to bash monsters because I really loved the characters and the Xillia universe.

column6: Cideko Air Keyboard Conqueror - Playstation 3
column13: After reciving a replacement, I still have a dud but now it's too late to return.
column14:
Bought one of these a while back and it didn't work at all. After replacing the device through Amazon, my urge to use it had passed so I only connected the replacement to verify that it worked as the first device wouldn't even connect. Since the replacement connected, I stupidly thought all was good.

I waited about a month and a half to finally try and use this hybrid controller again and it connected fine. I was able to get the mouse to "work" somehow as I couldn't quite determine what activated the motion controlled mouse or how to deactivate it.

As long as the mouse was not activated, most of the keyboard functions seemed to work. Anytime I accidentally activated the mouse functions I was not ever able to switch back to keyboard though.

At this point, I just figured I needed to learn how to use the device and all would be good.

So I connect the device to my PS3 and move the left analog stick and the devices activity light (light on controller that shows data communication) locks in the "on" position. I was not able to power the device off or do anything else from this point on. I disconnected the dongle and was able to power it off at this point.

I then Tried connecting the controller to a PC and installing the software. It didn't matter though. Anytime I touch an analog stick, the controller freezes.

I'm not stuck with a brick still searching for my controller keyboard combo.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Stealth 500X Premium Fully Wireless with Surround Sound Gaming Headset - Xbox One
column14:
Turtle Beach is a powerful brand; there is a reason they hold over 50% of the market share for console accessories and it generally has to do with the fact that they build solid, high quality headsets. With the announcement of the new Turtle Beach Elite 800X headset, we at Chalgyr's Game Room decided we would take a minute to share the love and wealth of some of their other gear, in this case the Stealth 500X for the Xbox One. Here is our take on this vaunted brand's oft-praised headset.
When I received the 500X I squealed a bit; there it was, a beautiful (if rather compact) box containing one of gaming's most popular brands and it was all mine. I popped open the box and just took it in; packed tightly into its shipping container, the 500X was sitting nice and snug with that new electronics smell. I loved it. Once I pulled out the few cables, receiver (did I mention it is fully wireless? Oh yeah, it is fully wireless and it is glorious), the headset and a few decals and the startup guide I was literally tripping over my coffee table in my haste to get it plugged in and charging. Fortunately the headset had about a 1/3 of the charge on it so I was able to plug it right into the Xbox One's rear USB port and the optical porta and I was on my wa.
The headset feels compact and tight; everything about it feels tense, like a beast waiting to be unleashed. The band is stiff, but pliable and never uncomfortable. The cups feel solid and are a little on the small side but after even four or five hours of The Withcer 3: Wild Hunt I felt no discomfort. The headset is gorgeous, with sleek lines, excellent accent piping, and feel solid and durable while maintaining a light and comfortable feel. Honestly Turtle Beach must have employed some sort of wizardry while building it as I have never seen/felt a headset that was both lightweight and heavy all in one, but the 500X is certainly that.
Even on the 1/3 charge I managed about 4 hours of gameplay before it died but I did notice that as the headset's battery came closer to no charge there was a definitive *click* in the audio; it was quite annoying but once I charged the headset and went back the following day to play some Battlefield: Hardline online I did not experience it again. (*UPDATE NOTE* After E3 finished I was playing some Gears of War Ultimate on the Xbox One and as the headset neared the end of its charge the clicking reappeared; I believe that it has to do with the headset not being able to adequately power the various modes, the wireless connection, the microphone, etc. and it is dropping the broadcast power to simply power the unit. It ONLY happens within the 5-10 minutes prior to the headset shutting off)

Within about five minutes of putting the headset on I could see why Turtle Beach is the market leader in console headsets; the 500X is rock solid and delivers some excellent 7.1 DTS surround sound and superior build quality. While there are numerous modes that you can set the headset in, essentially switching through pre-made equalizer settings, I did not find one that I loved more than the other (they were all quite nice), I personally could have gone for a little more bass, but to be fair I could always go for more bass.
Whether I was watching Avatar, playing The Witcher, or perusing YouTube, the Stealth 500X accurately recreates audio in crystal clear fashion. The real winner though? That would be the microphone. Most of the microphones I have tested for the Xbox One feel muted, shallow, or lacking any true depth of clarity. Not so with the Stealth 500X; crystal clean audio without the hiss or high popping of some of the more sensitive brands (PDP mics run a little hot) and when I would excitedly shout inot the microphone there was no distortion; it really is the best feature of the 500X (not to discount any of the other qualities though!).

Turtle Beach has had a stranglehold on the accessories market for years now and if the upcoming Elite 800X is anything like the Stealth 500X things will not be changing anytime soon. Their high manufacturing standards show in the rock solid and near-magical construction of the physical unit and the crisp, clean audio reproduction really do show that Turtle Beach has the gamer in mind when they develop and build their hardware and the Stealth 500X is an excellent representation of Turtle Beach's dedication to the gamer.oming Elite 800X is anything like the Stealth 500X things will not be changing anytime soon. Their high manufacturing standards show in the rock solid and near-magical construction of the physical unit and the crisp, clean audio reproduction really do show that Turtle Beach has the gamer in mind when they develop and build their hardware and the Stealth 500X is an excellent representation of Turtle Beach's dedication to the gamer.

Clearly an evolutionary edition of the controller, but still - it's absolutely the version Microsoft should have put out in the first place given the changes bring it inline with the ever-aging 360 controller. This new model changes the bumpers to be basically exactly like the 360 controller (i.e. you can press them anywhere, not just frustratingly on the edges like the first-gen XBOX One controller, and they're easier to press, too), and the controller adds a dedicated 3.5mm jack.

The rest of the controller is the same, which means if you like the general XBOX 360/One controller layout, you'll like this controller. Finally the bumpers are not a nuisance!

5 stars out of 5.

column6: Nyko Type Pad
column14: This Type Pad looks great on and works well with the PlayStation 4. It makes messaging friends and communicating with friends on MMORPGs like FFXIV so much easier. Setting it up is a breeze even if you are just slightly tech savvy. Even For those who don't consider themselves tech inclined, the Nyko Type Pad for PS4 comes with a thorough instruction manual that Will lead you step-by-step. The orange coloration of the text and symbols helps identify the keyboard in even dimly lit areas but the buttons do not glow-in-the-dark like even though it looks like it would, so using it in total darkness isn't ideal unless you're the type who memorized a QWERTY keyboard layout. This product has completely changed the way I approach sending messages on PlayStation 4. My Only real complaint isn't with the product itself but with the time it took to ship it. When I placed my order back in May, the product was set to arrive at the end of June. I pre-ordered it, thinking a preorder with secure me the item but then the end of June came along and suddenly the product information page read "Out of Stock" and the ETA for my Amazon Prime eligible order went from the end of June to "Between July 25th to August 3rd". This inconvenience did not impact my enjoyment of the product but the wait was way beyond the Amazon 2 Day shipping promise and seemed to undermine the point of preordering. What's The point of pre-ordering a product if you're not going to get it on the day it comes out, right? While I waited for the Nyko Type Pad, I could have went with a variety of other type pads that were readily available. Overall though, this is a review of the product itself and because of that, I stand by my 5 star rating ^_^

column6: Hatsune Miku: Project Diva f [Japanese Import] PS Vita
column13: Hatsune Miku has been pretty big in Japan for a while now
column14:
Hatsune Miku has been pretty big in Japan for a while now. Heck, Hatsune Miku is so big that she has her own live concerts around the world. If you do not know who Hatsune Miku is, she is a fictional singer that uses japanese vocals created by a vocaloid program. While Hatsune Miku has plenty of games in Japan, Hatsune Miku Project Diva F is her first video game debut in Western soil.

Hatsune Miku Project Diva F is rhythm game that has you pressing the PS Vita's face buttons and d-pad, as their respective icons fly onto the screen, the icons will play along in time to the music. There are also sections within the songs that require you to swipe the touch-screen in time to the music, which those icons appear as stars. The game's mechanics are a little bit more simple than others in the same genre.

Dependending on when you tap the buttons you will get different point values. There is awful, bad, safe, good, and cool. There is a Song Energy Gauge, that increases with every good and cool you get. If you do not keep up with the rhythm and get a bunch of awful and bad, the gauge will decrease and you will fail the song. Thankfully everything is perfectly responsive, which is a definite for games in this genre that relies so much on rhythm and skill.

This game will definitely put your rhythm skills to the test, some of the songs on the "Standard" difficulty can be tough. The game includes a "Beginner", "Standard", "Hard", and "Extreme" modes - the latter will make grown men cry. To make the game even more challenging you can enable special "Challenge Items" which let you earn more points. For example one of the most difficult challenges is called Perfectionist which will make you lose song energy if you get anything other than cool, ouch.

The game includes over 30 music tracks that each have their own music video. I have not mentioned this yet, though there is more than just Hatsune Miku. There are 6 different singers that appear in their own music videos, there are even some duets. These characters include,

- Hatsune Miku
- Kagamine Rin
- Kagamine Len
- Megurine Luka
- Kaito
- Meiko

All of the songs available on the base game are pretty darn catchy. After I would go through one of the many songs it would get stuck in my head and I could not stop humming it. There is a song in particular that all of you guys should know that is in the game, that song is Nyanyanyanyanyanyanya!

I mentioned that each song has their own music video, all of these videos are really well made and visually pleasing. Unfortunately the first time around you will not really be able to pay attention to the video since you have to keep all of your focus on the incoming button prompts. Luckily after you complete a song, you can the watch song's music video with no distractions in the "Watch Video" mode.

Outside of the "Rhythm Game" mode there are plenty of other modes to play around with. Some pointless and some enjoyable. The some enjoyable modes include "Edit", "Diva Room", and "Shop".

The "Edit" mode is surprisingly deep, it lets you create your own music videos, button prompts, and dances to any of the songs in the game or you can even use your own .MP3 collection. You can customize the background, choose any of the six characters and customize their dances and even their facial expression during every second of the song.

The "Diva Room" and "Shop" go hand in hand with each other. In the "Diva Room" you can visit each of the singers apartment rooms and interact with the characters. You can become each singers friend by buying them gifts, playing Rock-Paper-Scissors, or petting them - the latter is strange, although that is not the reason I am recommending this mode.

In the shop you can buy items with "Diva Points" that you earn by playing the game. You can purchase items that customize all six of the characters and their rooms. You can buy a bunch of different accessories and clothing, some cool and some goofy. The characters will even wear the clothing during the music videos and they will walk around in their apartment with the clothing on. You can buy a T.V. and a photo album for the apartments, which let you view and make playlists of the songs in the game and view photos that you unlocked.

The pointless modes include the "AR" modes that let you have AR concerts and take AR pictures. Some people might be into this kind of stuff, though I was not too impressed with them. I was also not impressed with the load times, they appear with everything you press on the main menu. They are not terribly long but annoying.

Hatsune Miku Project Diva F is a great game that most fans of the rhythm genre could enjoy. The gameplay might be too simplistic for experts of the genre, as it is pretty basic compared to other games. For people that are interested in a basic rhythm game there are plenty of songs to play which all of them are fun to play, challenging, catchy to listen to, and fun to watch. The game will give you plenty of replay value with the multiple difficulties to master and all of the other extras that the game has.h "Diva Points" that you earn by playing the game. column6: Nintendo Wii U Deluxe Set: Super Mario 3D World and Nintendo Land Bundle - Black 32 GB
column13: Overlooked System. The System That The Casual/Nintendo 64/GameCube Gamer Woud Love.
column14:
I'm quite the gamer and I was really reluctant on buying a Nintendo system only because Microsoft and Sony have been dominating the industry in the last 5-10 years with the PS3/Xbox 360 and now Xbox One/PS4 era. Of course, this topic is very subjective depending on the way you have looked at gaming in the last 10 years. Sony and Microsoft have taken the reigns on pushing hardware capabilities and upgrading technology to push out Next-Gen graphics/experiences, which they have done quite well at.

Nintendo has taken a totally unique approach, taking gambles by integrating different visionary technologies such as motion control and tablet compatability and bringing that to a greater light to the gaming industry. The goal was to reach out to a wider audience, which they have done quite successfully. They have been making very ambitious moves since the introduction of the nunchuck controllers, and focusing on the interactive gaming experience within the home rather than pushing the envelope in gameplay/graphics sophisitication. This move has arguably put Nintendo as the King once again of last gen's consoles, however created quite a split and dilemna for both hardcore and casual gamers alike. If you wanted to be well immersed in the gameplay and the cinematics, you were a Sony/Microsoft man. If you wanted the ability to really share the experience to a larger group such as a family or a party audience to enjoy together, you probably wanted to get a Wii. Nintendo is a user-friendly experience.

I digress. The reason why I bought this system is simply due to the fact that there were still games from the Nintendo franchise that I dearly loved, as well as people in my life that I wanted to share my gaming experiences with but were unable to do so because of the learning curve these other games have for the casual gamer. It's hard to capture the interest of your girlfriend or certain family members who aren't quite interested in games or don't have thetime of day to really play to begin to learn the controls of an FPS/RPG/MMO/etc. However, it's very easy to get into a Super Mario, Mario Kart, Wii Sports, etc. That's where Nintendo thrives. They make it very easy and accessible for everybody. So, buying a bundle such as this is nice because it comes with games that either I or a group of friends can hop right on and start to enjoy away. I also ended up going to Gamestop to pick up a couple of other items such as extra controllers and games so that I also have things I could enjoy for myself or with other core gaming friends I know online who play Smash, Splatoon, Zelda, etc. It's really nostalgic in some ways for me going back to my childhood and the Nintendo 64 seeing some of these other game characters that we grew up with still around and growing into what they are today. It's cool.

One drawback I have on the Nintendo Wii U is the fact that since you have the tablet controller, you have two power adapters that need to be plugged in now instead of one. It's nice that the controller does come with stands to use for charging and/or display. Haven't bought too many games for the Wii U yet so hard drive storage hasn't been an issue for me yet. Another drawback that I feel is quite a letdown on the Nintendo consoles is that there is no ethernet port for those who like having wired connections to play online. It's cool that there are I believe 4 USB ports on the Nintendo, but I feel ethernet ports should be a default option in this day and age. I did buy an ethernet adapter on amazon as well that you can plug into one of the USBs to get that wired connection capability. The latency improves alot with this as the Wifi isn't too great on this machine.

Games such as Smash when played online rely heavily on the players internet connections, rather than actual dedicated servers that they would have for big games such as Call of Duty or Street Fighter. You may have good internet in your home, but that may not mean much if the latency on your system picks up on your Wii U. It's weird.

I like the fact that Nintendo atleast went 1080p on this system. Kind of sad to hear that Wii U hasn't done that great in sales and has already announced working on a new system soon I believe called the NX. So IN MY OPINION, if you're not really that interested in getting a Wii U and you can wait about a year or so, I'm sure Nintendo's next move might be a show stopper. I'm praying on it. Wii U has been greatly overlooked but you have to give them props for 2 things.

1) Being able to connect with a wider audience.
2) Backwards compatability (gaming and hardware) haha.

column6: Ninja Gaiden 3: Razor's Edge - Nintendo Wii U
column13: \ And I\"m pretty sure even Ryu"
column14: This game has a potty mouth. I felt uncomfortable playing this game because ever five seconds, the enemy swears by loudly saying "F*** YOU!" And I"m pretty sure even Ryu, the playable character, is muttering the F-word because he wishes you played better. Normally I'm not phased by swearing but I live in an apartment now...  The game is violent and it demands you execute the enemy with extreme methods. I noticed very little sneaking about in the game, again due to my poorly playing it. It reminded me of the classic game series on NES but "Ancient Ship of Doom" this is not. It's a shame that the other games in the  NG  series are not on Wii U nor the 360 exclusive Dead or Alive franchise which also stars my main man, Ryu!  Though I have to say even though he wears his modern costume for the series, but it doesn't seem legit. Razor's Edge doesn't make much sense. For some reason Ryu's arm is possessed or something by a blood thirsty demon. You button mash the crud out of the controller's buttons and stuff happens, but maybe too fast for me to understand what I am doing. I sorta felt myself going into a trance sort of and smiled at all the gore and blood flying around.   The one thing it does have that its older siblings on NES had is "cheap" difficulty where many of the enemies will use kamikaze attacks, tackling Ryu and blowing themselves up with a bomb. So you have to just mash the buttons until an enemy is bloody, THEN mash them extra hard 'til they are dismembered by Ryu.

column6: inFAMOUS Second Son - PlayStation 4
column14:
I've given inFamous Second Son 5 stars because it succeeds in being a very entertaining game, and I really enjoyed it. It plays like all the other inFamous games, although each one has a slightly different gimmick in the powers of the main character - but this time time you have a lot more!

The story sees an unwilling character suddenly given superpowers, and like in the last games, you have opportunities to choose being doing good and doing evil. The things that work well are the cast of characters who are all good and well acted. They also look like real people. Like, really real people who don't have model good looks or super fit bodies. I'm impressed by this nod to realism. The game plays very easily with a selection of powers that you can develop equally or just concentrate on your favourites. With a little patience you can defeat all the enemies you encounter with relative ease. Bosses are more challenging but will all fall if you pay attention to what you're doing. Auto saves are plentiful, and it's especially nice having mid-fight checkpoints in the longer boss battles. On this note, the main villain of the game is an absolute monster, really well characterised and acted, and I played the whole game specifically looking forward to bringing her down!

The scenery looks great, the game is loosely based on Seattle although it's not quite as awesome as the copy of Chicago in "Watchdogs", it does have some of the city's flavour. It's not a super long game, but it's never boring, and I really liked it.

column6: Insten Dual Charging Station Charger + 2 Battery Packs w/ LED Light For Wii / Wii U Remote Controller,- Retail Packaging
column14:
Before reviewing the product, I need to say the seller - eForCity - was great. Responsive, helpful, willing to make things right even at their expense. Kudos to them. Unfortunately, the product left me very disappointed.

The main issue is the battery packs seem to be manufactured by people who can't comprehend how it will "snap" into the Wii remote. When installing each one, the part that makes contact with one of the batteries can easily break, as it's not angled the right way to slide in. The first one I put in was a struggle, but the second one broke. eForCity sent me a free replacement, and that one would have also broken had I not used pliers to reshape it a bit.

The second issue is once nestled in the charger, I've found the remotes can easily lose contact and stop charging. Unfortunately, when that happens it turns blue, which is what it does when they're finished charging.

Finally, you can't leave the charger plugged in unless you don't mind blinding blue LED light 24-7. It stays on even when there's nothing in the cradles, and there's no on/off switch. It needs to be unplugged.

Considering all the hassles, it's probably easier to just use rechargeable batteries.

column6: The Elder Scrolls Online
column13: Lots of time invested, absolutely no return: Extremely unrewarding gameplay.
column14: Played for a very long time, within the upper 2 digits of hours, and I am totally sick of the game. Be it the dull, repetitive side quests, uninspired main, plain hack n slash combat with little reward, and the game feeling like it wants to look every last cent out of you with pointless content additions and needless subscriptions. Servers are clumsy, and I felt myself getting booted off every 45 minutes at the longest stretch of time. Scenery is quite attractive in many places, but exploration feels pointless and unrewarding due to total lack of "true elderscrolls-y" content, like small caverns, smashed camp sites and quality loot. Game's "lore" material is lazily added in by packing "lorebooks" in every corner of the world.  Weapons and armor are interesting enough to look at, and the crafting system is well out together, although very confusing when starting out. Loot in the world is never anything interesting; no mystical named weapons and armor like what is found in true Elder Scrolls titles, and gold can be very hard to come by considering the cost of most all in game items. Justice system is there... but it is poor. Guards cannot be killed and lockpicking makes players stand; breaking out of stealth for all to see...  In all honesty, this may sound like a massive whine-fest but there really aren't many pros to outweigh the almost endless cons. A real shame too, considering Bethesda put their name on this nightmare. Absolutely stay away from this title, you won't miss out on anything besides getting made a chump of by these big publishers milking every last time out of you.  3/10: wait until it's $5 in a few years, it may we worth the money by then.

column6: PDP AG7 True Wireless Headset for Xbox One
column13: Great sounding headphones, but microphone volume is lacking
column14:
[[VIDEOID:a9ebb8e7454df6453f81e67fa32070eb]] The AG7's are a great sounding wireless headset for the Xbox One. It has the added bonus of also working with Windows computers through the included USB dongle and will also work with anything else that supports a standard 1/8\\\ headphone/headset adapter. That includes mobile devices running Android as well as iPhones and Macs.

The bass is loud and evident even in the standard mode. There's a second audio mode that gives a little more boom but it comes at the expense of overall audio clarity. The default mode is good enough for me.

The biggest issue with AG7, however, is the included mic. The pickup level is very low, meaning you are going to sound very distant during in-game chats. I found this to be the case both with the Xbox One and my Windows PC using the wireless dongle. Plugging in via an analog cable to my Mac resulted in louder audio, so I suspect there's a setting on the dongle that's limiting the mic's audio output.

The mic mute indicator is also confusing. For some reason PDP decided the light on the mic should indicate which audio mode the headphones are in, not the mute status of the microphone. It will indicate mute with a blink every minute or so, but it would have made more sense to have the mic light up red when muted. It also won't mute when it's retracted back into its holder.

If they can fix the mic issues I will rate this set higher. It really does sound very good but it's not the total package it is currently advertising itself to be."
