column14: In terms of functionality it is probably premature for me to choose between four and five stars, but I am giving it the five star rating because having tried the main competition this seems clearly the best for what it is -- a simple non-powered USB hub that turns a two-USB port system into a five-port system. Was a great relief to get this because I was banging my head over the fact that our PS3 games that warranted multiple plug-ins couldn't be played, and I couldn't find a USB hub extension that worked reliably. column6: The Legend of Zelda: Skyward Sword
column13: however it played just fine in American Wii U I bought in 2014
column14:
Item shipped was UAE, Malaysia, Singapore version of the game, however it played just fine in American Wii U I bought in 2014. I'm not sure if it will work for all systems, I've heard other purchasers say it didn't work for them, but I had no such problem. The game is in English and is really indistinguishable from the American version as far as I can tell.

With all that said, this is game is fantastic. I put off playing for several years because I didn't purchase a Wii. My desire to play classic Nintendo titles and see what new they had to offer led me to purchase a Wii U and gave me the chance to catch up on 10+ years of Wii titles I'd missed. This game is a gem in the Legend of Zelda series and stays true to it's roots while implementing a really fun control system that actually works pretty well. I thought it would be gimmicky to swing the Wiimote like sword but they've done a really good job with it. I highly recommend this game for Legend of Zelda fans and anyone looking for a great Nintendo Wii experience.

column13: If you're looking for a competitive game, just keep looking.
column14:
I bought this game in high hopes of reliving the classic living room situations Mario Party brought me and my childhood friends in front of the N64. This game simply just did not do that.

Mario Party 10 puts all of the characters in a "car". Each player still rolls the dice but each player rides together. It is isn't really the same game when the game is based around this.

Bowser Party was awesome, but hardly makes this game worth buying. My gripes with this mode was there are only three boards.

Nintendo has a lot of room for improvement with this one. I was expecting much, much more seeing how Nintendo had so much momentum with the launch of Amiibo going forward. The Amiibo mode for this game is very confusing and puzzling.

This game is NOT for the competitive player. If I had children I could see myself playing this with them in a fun cooperative manner. For adults who want to give each other hell and dominate, stick to Smash Bros.

column6: NAtURAL DOCtRINE - PlayStation Vita
column13: Not for the faint of heart
column14:
I was excited about this game when I first hear about it and saw trailers, but in actually playing this, I was a little let down.
To be honest, I am not sure why though.

I was not expecting HD graphics on a Vita version (although I do not believe the PS3/4 versions have any better).
You do not buy these type of games for stunning visuals, but to have yourself challenged and feel rewarded for the time you put into it.

This is not a typical RPG or strategy game, but more of a hybrid.
Combat can be grueling and one mistake on your part can lead to decimation - quickly.
Its rather unforgiving in that realm.

The main concept is chaining attacks and part members together to defeat the almost always sea of monsters that outnumber your at least 3 to 1 (in a good situation).
You can also chain them to defend on another and this is just as essential to the part survival.
You do not get to save until the dungeon/battle is over, but it does save "checkpoints" during the battle.
So if you make a mistake, you have start over from a checkpoint, which can be grueling.
It almost forces you to be perfect, which can be OK at times, but just seems punishing in this game.

This is definitely not a game for everyone or for those with little patience.

The RPG system is limited in the amount of upgrades you can give your characters in terms of skills.
Gear has to be found mainly by running the dungeons over and over.

The "magic" system costs a very valuable and rare resource that is acquired every time you loot a chest or sell and item, however all spells cast are drained from the same universal pool and cannot be regenerated by "resting" or finding an Inn.
This makes you value it much more and be very wise with the use of it.

The challenge factor is definitely present in this game.
This game is definitely a unique idea and was put intopractice very well.
The link system seems so simple at first, but can easily become so very complex and confusing.

Overall, for the price this game currently goes for, I would definitely say to a hardcore gamer to give this a shot to experience a very unique style RPG
If you are the average RPG player, stay away, spend your money on Persona or Y's or one of the Tales games.

column6: Borderlands 2
column13: If Diablo and a first-person shooter fell in love and made a baby
column14:
Borderlands 2 is a first-person shooter with a mixture of role-playing elements that make it stand out in today‚Äôs oversaturation of generic first-person shooters. You play as one of 6 vault hunters, each with their own unique skill tree and special abilities. You complete quests, beat enemies, defeat bosses, collect various kinds of loot, and gain experience points to level up your character's various skills and abilities. If Diablo and a first-person shooter fell in love and made a baby, Borderlands 2 would be that baby.

Some people might fear that the controls will not be all that good considering the the PS Vita has less buttons than its PS3 counterpart. Well controlling the game works just fine on the PSVita. I can do everything that I can do with the PS3 controller with ease. The game has many preset controller layouts for you to mess around with or you can just change everything you want with a completely customizable layout. Some functions use the back touch pad and it is not terrible. For you to use the back touch pad you have to touch closer to the middle (From the left or to the right.) to activate one of the two functions so there should be no accidental presses, at least from how I hold my PS Vita. I customized my control layout to be more like Killzone: Mercenary controls and it controls just fine.

Borderlands is known for it's unique cel-shading styled graphics and the graphics look great on the PS Vita. I was amazed that they were able to recreate one of my favorite PS3 games on the Vita and still make it look good. Do not think it is the same quality that you will find on your PS3 though. There had to be some changes so it would run on a portable system. The draw distances are shorter, not as much detail, and no ragdoll physics for enemy deaths ( They just explode with blood going everywhere and the body disappears.). To me, even with those tradeoffs the game still looks great.

The game has a ton of content to play around with. There are a variety of different quests that kept me hooked on for the entire time. Heck, I still have to do more side-quests and complete the DLC content that came out for it. Speaking of the DLC, this version comes with 6 of the content packs that came out for the PS3 version. You will get the first two campaign add-ons, (Captain Scarlett and her Pirate‚Äôs Booty and Mr. Torgue‚Äôs Campaign of Carnage), Gaige the Mechromancer and Krieg the Psycho characters, along with the Vault Hunter Upgrade pack and the Collector‚Äôs Edition Pack, which increase the level cap to 61 and gives you some new heads and skins for your characters. Unfortunately absent are two campaign DLCs, "Tiny Tina‚Äôs Assault on Dragon Keep" and "Sir Hammerlock's Big Game Hunt"; also missing is the "Ultimate Vault Hunter Upgrade 2" which increases the level cap to 72 and the all of the "Headhunter" packs.

The game even comes packed in with online cooperative play. Though it might be a deal breaker to some, it is limited to 2-players. I do not mind it though as I think it's good enough for the lesser amounts of enemies in a area compared to the PS3 version (PS3 version might of had 14 enemies there but the PSVita only has 10 for an example.). Plus it's less people trying to steal your precious loot.

Playing through the game I did notice some bugs and framerate drops. The drops in the framerate do not happen enough for it to ruin my experience with the game, although it is a little worse in co-op. Do not get me wrong, it could be better. Hopefully future patches can get rid of some of the framerate drops. The only other problem I had would be the load times. The PS3 had long load times also and the PS Vita's load times are just little longer that is it, just a little.

Borderlands 2 for the PS Vita is nearly identical to the Borderlands 2 that was released a couple of years ago. So if you already own it then you are just paying for the option to play it on the go. If you never played it, definitely think about getting this game. You'll be getting a game filled with a huge amount of content that you can take wherever you go. Borderlands 2 is a great portable version of the console game with a few minor issues.ying for the option to play it on the go. If you never played it, definitely think about getting this game. You'll be getting a game filled with a huge amount of content that you can take wherever you go. Borderlands 2 is a great portable version of the console game with a few minor issues.

column6: Game Party 2 - Nintendo Wii
column13: This wasn't even good the first time...
column14:
Have you ever played a video game that you thought was such a terrible experience that you wished it hadn't ever existed or hoped that not many people have caught onto it? Unfortunately, Game Party is the shovelware series that millions of Wii owners fell victim to in the first place, allowing it to leech onto our beloved console even more for clueless, innocent buyers to purchase for family-friendly fun only to fall to their knees in frustration from the near-brokenness of what they just purchased.

Game Party 2 continues the trainwreck-of-a-minigame-collection idea that Game Party gladly used to scam victims out of their wallets. There are eleven activities this time, but considering that around nine of those eleven share almost literally the same exact control scheme on paper ("Press A in this stance to prepare tossing the object, then go over to THIS OTHER stance and RELEASE A to toss the object!"), it's pretty much all just a bunch of filler.

Development on Game Party 2 was obviously as lazy as ever; as if the reused idea of throwing games wasn't enough, the motion controls are slightly improved, but are still just about nonfunctional at times, and while I'd like to say the graphics still look like as if they were from the Playstation 1-era, I think that would be insulting that gem of a console, as I've seen it do better in terms of graphic capabilities. The sound is....well, it's sound, but much of it at least was reused from the last game.

Honestly, who keeps thinking it's a good idea to shell out these wretched "party" games that aren't even accessible to their target audience thanks to their horrendous controls and lousy presentation? The most confusing aspect of this is that FarSight Studios is a development team with talent, if their amazing pinball video games are of any consideration. If anything, you should buy Pinball Hall of Fame: The Williams Collection for your Wii instead of any one of these Game Party travesties.ty travesties.

column6: Godzilla - PlayStation 4
column14:
As a game for everyone this one isses the mark entirely. This is not a gane meant to be enjoyed by all or attract new fans. This is a fan service to diehard Godzilla fans like myself. With that being said the game is poorly bananced in the beginning but all of the monster become stronger as they grow taller.

The monsters animations, models, etc look very much spot on and Godzilla has never looked better. The recreation of our favorite fight scenes and the mechanics - you move just like the monsters! - make the game well worth purchasing if you are a fan.

next the city graphics have their moments but for the most part the maps are still too small and they look like well miniature sets so I know that was the developers intentions, but had the cities looked just like the trailers most game review sites would have given it a much higher score.

Now to conclude my review if you loved Godzilla as a kid, you will love this game.I have already put 30 plus hours into it. Gamespot harping on the lack of content yet other games getting smashed in 6 hours get better reviews? 2d side scrollers get better reviews? bottom line this game didnt have a big budget and its fun to play. This is the best fab service to Godzilla fans in years.

column6: Razer Kraken 7.1 Chroma - Surround Sound USB Gaming Headset (Certified Refurbished)
column13: Solid performance for a great price.
column14:
I have used these for about a month now and I am very happy. my previous headset was a Logitech G230, a very average headset. These headphones opened up sounds I had never heard from my video games before. Frequency response is excellent. Build quality feels solid all the way around. I wish the earcups were a bit bigger, but the foam used is soft and comfortable. The mic actually coils up neatly when not in use, and has a red LED light on the end to tell you if it is muted. Headset arrived in a simple brown box. No software was included, but following instructions, got the Synapse software from the Razer website in 2 minutes. Everything worked perfectly out of box, and I didn't notice any scuffs or scratches on the headset.

Pros: Excellent sound, construction feels solid, good mic clarity, nice LEDs on the ear cups, heavy duty USB cable
Cons: Bigger ear cups would be nice.

I paid $65 for these, and I feel they are an excellent value for that amount of money.

column6: Suikoden 3
column14:
Years ago my above friend did something that I‚Äôve never looked back on or once regretted. He sold me his PS1, which was my move away from Nintendo based consoles for quite a while. Sometime after this he introduced me to what is pretty much a cult classic: Suikoden II. Fast forward another few years and I bought my brother‚Äôs PS2, making it my own. Louis came over throwing Suikoden III at me before he was heading out of town for a weekend. While I enjoyed Suikoden II, it to me didn‚Äôt hold a candle to Suikoden III, which was my favorite entry in the series until the release of the fifth. Back once again, Konami have re-released Suikoden III on the PSN, making it playable for both the PSIII and the Vita. While physically sitting on my shelf, it has been too long since I‚Äôve picked it up. Being able to review it now is an honor.

Suikoden III was special for more reasons than the above stated. The third entry into the series went through many changes from the previous two as it took advantage of the power of the newer PlayStation 2 moving from a sprite base over to 3D models and environments. This allowed for characters to show expression in more than just dialog boxes, creating a much more of a cinematic approach within gameplay like a lot of that era tried for before voice acting became more commonplace. While graphically moving in another direction, an anime-like opening cutscene was still used as a lot of RPGs did, but was now in even higher quality both in terms of sound and visuals. Exceeding Love, the opening theme of Suikoden III, perfectly fits the opening sequence and the overall feel of the story which is deep, rich, and at a lot of times heart heavy with the actions that some must take whether they want to or not.

Having gone a different route than the rest of the series, Suikoden III is the only entry in the series that features three main protagonists with separate story lines as well as several playable sub plots. Now while the idea of separate plot lines can be daunting at times since generally what happens is that players would be replaying the same events over and over for maybe one or two different story segments, this is far from the case. Each of our three characters all have chapters of their own and can be selected from the starting Trinity Site in which players are brought back to on the return of a finished chapter. This site allows for the player to choose the next chapter of either the same character or that of another. With this in mind, it is not possible to finish the entire story with solely one character as everything is intertwined. Each main character story must reach a certain point in order for everything to continue moving forward again never leaving any doubts as to what is happening.

Actually, that‚Äôs a lie! There are a lot of moments in which players might be thinking ‚Äúwhat is going on?‚Äù until much later when all of the pieces truly fall into place. Here are three completely separate people, from completely separate backgrounds and cultures. Biases, hatreds, and misgivings between some is more than expected when one group tends to think of the others as uncivilized barbarians. GENERALLY though, following all chapters will paint a proper picture of the events unfolding as the chapters happen at roughly the same time or slightly prior showing how things came to the point that you are seeing or have seen. For anyone not having played, even if it is a much older game, I‚Äôm going to say that I‚Äôm not touching anything story related as just about anything could be a spoiler for something else! One thing that should be noted however is that being an older RPG, save points are not exactly the most common at times and when you sit down to play, prepare for several hours worth of game time as sometimes, that‚Äôs the minimum between various cutscenes and battle segments.

Combat is probably one of my favorite parts of Suikoden III. Using a six member party, players set up their characters in groups of two for a total of three groups. The manner in which groups perform depend entirely upon who is paired with whom at times as it can make essentially a landslide of difference in battle capabilities. Actions that can be taken in battle range from physical over to magical in abilities as well as the option to simply attack. Using a form of movement, the player‚Äôs party and the enemy party will need to move between themselves and each other in order to hit their targets. Units that are mounted on horseback essentially have more chance of making it if there are a lot of enemies on the field in comparison to someone on foot.

Where things get really cool is when you start collecting more characters for larger parties and experiment with who gets paired. The best example of this is one of the main characters Hugo and his griffon Fubar. Side by side in different groups they will go about attacking as they see fit alongside their partner or solo depending on the size of the group. When paired together however, Hugo rides Fubar which leaps up into the air and flies to the target and together they do a lot more damage at the expense that they only perform one action. With a total of 108 different possible characters also known as the series‚Äô Stars of Destiny, there are a lot of possibilities in mixing and matching characters for various outcomes.

On completion of a successful battle, every present character receives experience points. I know right? Who would have thought with this being an RPG and all. Why this is a bit more important is that only two series that I can think of have done away with incremental experience caps and instead decided that characters simply need 1000xp in order to level. The first is the Suikoden series and the second was the .Hack series. Just 1000xp? That‚Äôs it? That‚Äôs it. Obviously nothing is ever that easy though as we‚Äôve all come to know. Each character level is a simple 1000xp with modifiers that are put into place as they gain levels. At a certain point in time it no longer becomes possible to level off of certain creatures as there is essentially nothing left to learn and experience must be found elsewhere in more danger stricken territories.

Like Combat, Skill and Magic work interestingly enough. Using a form of letter grade, both of these types of abilities generally start off in the range of D, E, F, which would mean that the character has an idea of what their doing, but they aren‚Äôt great at it. Using points gathered in combat, either type of ability can be upgraded at a shop that offers its services in that field. Upgrading one of these abilities allows for several things. The first is that especially in the terms of magic, spells can be cast more times as the stock of what a character can perform before a rest in increased. Secondly the higher abilities within that tree are unlocked allowing for more powerful spells to be cast. Lastly though, this modifies the casting speed time in which a character requires to perform these actions within battle without worry as it is possible to be interrupted.

Not every character is good at everything which should be kept in mind when looking at possible skills or magic to add. With 108 different people that makes a lot of sense. In the shops there is the ability to ask the owner to check compatibility. This will allow the player to better grasp how they should develop up a character. Some character for example can never be better than a D-Rank for water magic while others that excel can go all the way to either an A, A+. or S-Rank. If mistakes are made through or it simply makes more sense to add a different skill or magic type, these can be forgotten for another cost in order to start all over again. Not everything can be forgotten just as not everything can be learned. Finding out which is which is just as important.

Suikoden III was released as a PS2 Classic and not as an HD Remake meaning that nothing was touched in regards to visuals, menus, resolutions, etc. The anime cutscene still looks absolutely impressive as anime does tend to age very well. As for the rest of the graphics it should be noted that everything was originally designed for a 4:3 ratio before widescreens became a thing. I know right? How did we ever manage‚Ä¶

If the default settings are left as they are, there could be a bit of wanting for sharper graphics as things can look a bit edgy and the character dialog is somewhat blurry. Having a PSIII that dates back to before Sony decided to remove the chip that ran the backwards compatibility, I‚Äôve had more than enough time to get familiar with possible options to improve the older generation of games. Thankfully those options are still there on newer PS3s through the software emulation as I‚Äôve had Suikoden III running on a slim model. The particular option is ‚Äúsmoothing‚Äù which fixes the above issues making everything much more enjoyable to look at even if the whole screen can‚Äôt be taken up. This is important to mention as most people may not think to even look around for something like that and be disappointed as the quality is not up to today‚Äôs standards when it can be.

Suikoden III as a game is a stellar RPG that does everything right. Suikoden III as a PS2 classic is still just as good even if something tiny like aspect ratios prevent from having full widescreens. Combined together, the experience is a great one and more than worth it for both old fans and new players as each entry of the Suikoden series happens in the same world but each act as a stand alone short of some very tiny details here and there.s a simple 1000xp with modifiers that are put into place as they gain levels. column6: TRON Wired Controller for PS3 Collector's Edition
column14:
Beauty over function is what you're getting here. She sure looks pretty but is nowhere near the quality or convenience of the official PlayStation controllers.

1. It's wired. Understandable, given it contains Tron inspired blue lights, which are always on. The cord is approximately 10' long, so you'll have plenty of length to work with.
2. The analog sticks feel laggy. Very unresponsive and sluggish, like playing with lag when your connection is rock solid. Would not recommend for fast paced action games...I tried, it's horrible.
3. D Pad also sticky & laggy. These have quite a long throw and much higher profile than the standard controller and are at times unresponsive due to the longer/harder press.

On the plus side, it is a beautiful controller but looks don't equal performance. I've had mine for 5 years and it has spent all of its time in my unused peripheral basket.

column6: Batman Arkham Origins
column14: Never having played an Arkham game before I must say this was not a good first experience. I've seen gameplays of Arkham Knight and the big selling point for me was the ability to cruise around Gotham in the Batmobile. I assumed that I would have the same experience or at least with another Bat-vehicle in Origins. Well unless I have not progressed in the game far enough that doesn't seem to be possible. Also not even 2 hours in I'm noticing some glaring flaws. For starters the combat system is broken and not at all what I'd expect Batman to be capable of. Countering is spotty and the slow motion finisher feels rushed in order to add eye candy to the game. As for gameplay, the scroll menu using the D-pad for batarangs and such is near impossible to navigate. Im not kidding when I say I spent nearly 8 minutes just trying to get the hacking thing to pop up. Which brings me to my next point. That bat hacker thing is totally unnecessary and almost impossible to use. Another gripe: Navigating around Gotham is not what I'd expect as all you can do is run (bad idea unless you want a fight every 5 seconds) or slowly glide from one building to the next grappling here and there. Again I'm not to far in maybe you get a bat-cycle or something but so far navigating from place to place is tedious and cumbersome. The lack of mini map further complicates things tenfold. Minor gripe: The graphics are great during the cutscenes not so much during gameplay. Felt like I was playing PS2 All in all I'm really not happy with this game and am even skeptical about getting Arkham Knight.

column6: TRITTON 720+ 7.1 Surround Headset for Xbox 360 and PS3
column13: It has been malfunctioning one month after purchase
column14: These were nice and easy to setup on my ps4 by following the given instructions. The sad thing is about a month into my usage the SVM feature quit working almost all together. I believe its a short or some issue with the wiring because if I bend the wiring leading up to my headset a certain way I hear a pop and I can hear myself but with a significant decrease in volume. If the wire moves I hear an even louder (ear-deafening) pop in the headset, and it would quit working again. Not only this but when I speak to people my microphones volume would all of a sudden drop as if I was whispering into my headset. Looking into the voice volume control setting in the PS4 and with the same settings I have always had, the system (PS4) barely registered that I was talking at all. The only fix was to un-plug the USB cable that runs from the controller box (The thing that looks like a router) to my PS4 and reinsert the cable back in. I have contacted Tech support on the issue but I have yet to hear back from them. So far its been 3 days.

column6: Onechanbara Z2 Chaos
column13: The combat is just pure fun
column14:
I‚Äôm a certified hack ‚Äòn‚Äô slash expert! Okay, ‚Äúexpert‚Äù is probably a bit of a fraudulent stretch. In fact, I certainly and objectively suck compared to the player who can perform a no-damage 30 minute speed-run of Bayonetta on the hardest difficulty whilst, for added challenge and absurdity, her hands are oiled and confined within 14oz boxing gloves.

But I do play and enjoy a variety of hack ‚Äòn‚Äô slash titles -- those I can manage to get my mediocre mitts on -- from the mainstream to the niche and everything in between. These can range from mass peasant-spanking simulators like the Dynasty Warriors franchise to anger aptitude tests such as Ninja Gaiden Black. And after having the fortune of experiencing Onechanbara Z2: Chaos, I must tell you, my possible fellow hack ‚Äòn‚Äô slash aficionados, while wafting the energizing scent of my own self-satisfaction:

If you don‚Äôt mind the game‚Äôs arguably welcome single-minded focus on insurmountable babes, impossibly durable bikinis, superabundant undead bloodshed, and don‚Äôt take issue with incredibly linear level design as well as imbalances in level length, then you will discover a combat system in Z2: Chaos that, while not as complex combat-wise as the likes of Bayonetta or Devil May Cry 4, can be just as satisfying as its contemporaries within the genre.

The story is an entertaining mixture of surreal nonsense: Two groups, the Vampiric Clan and the Baneful Bloodline, have been mocking each other‚Äôs ridiculously ample bustlines and swiping swords at one another‚Äôs bikini breastplates for decades to determine which group is superior. But when a greater evil threatens to swarm the world in a mass of undead viciousness, two sets of sisters from the opposing groups decide to collaborate, traveling the world to eviscerate inexplicable henchmen in a stylishly frenzied manner. There is camaraderie, there are cowboy hats and there are a few jokes about overly ample bosoms channeled through a narrative told in still comic book panels. There is a girl in a dress who attempts to bonk our heroines in their faces with a spiked club because... I don‚Äôt know? She‚Äôs apparently jealous of how they retain favorable hip-to-waist ratios despite eating like bear cubs deserted on a salmon farm (which is a almost certainly incorrect speculation on my part).

The tale and its accompanying dialogue may be silly and campy and a bit scatterbrained, for sure. However these traits allows the game to make its awesome, ridiculous ‚Äúbikinis slay the undead‚Äù premise a triple combination of lighthearted, occasionally self-aware, and charmingly low-budget, characteristics that compliment a few hours of leisurely stupidity after a stressful day of deadlines or competitive diaper changing (if you‚Äôre a maniacally organized parent, you might be into that type of diversion). If you require a storyline that‚Äôs more cohesive, coherent, and thoughtful, however, then, well, you probably wouldn‚Äôt be interested in an adventure about bikini samurais to begin with.

If the story does happen to be too bare for expectations, then perhaps the combat will improve upon and make up for its impropriety. For as a masterful team of four ‚Äì Kagura and Saaya, half-blood sisters from the Vampiric Clan; Aya and Saki, sisters of the Baneful Bloodline ‚Äì you sprint from hallway to enemy horde, releasing whatever catharsis that may be harbored within with a variety of extravagant slices, punches, and special attacks that give the word ‚Äúpandemonium‚Äù gainful employment.

Now, each character has a primary weapon, a secondary weapon, and sub weapon, all of which feel unique and can be accessed on the fly with the press of a button before, after, or in between any combo set you desire, allowing said combos to be pretty customizable in terms of attack order.

For example, you have the basic weak, strong, and sub-weapon attacks ‚Äì which are assigned to square, triangle, and circle, respectively ‚Äì and when executing a weak combo sequence, which consists of tapping square in succession, you have the freedom to change up this basic combo by adding a few strong and sub weapon attacks into the mix. And when you return to the weak combo, your attack continues from where it left off in the original sequence, whether it was on the third or tenth animation of said sequence before you initiated the change up. So, while the move list may not be expansive, the combat can be a joy to experiment with for the sake of challenging yourself amidst a blouse-ripping five-hundred hit combo.

Skirmishes become even more chaotic (hence the game‚Äôs title, I suppose) when character switching, team attacks, and special attacks are set loose into the battleground: Pressing up or down on the D-pad immediately switches characters; smashing the touch-pad like a dishonored sells-word unleashes all four girls, each one synchronized to your input, each swing of their weapons colorfully coursed by the girls‚Äô unique auras at an unwavering 60 fps; and simultaneously pressing triangle and circle sets off each warriors‚Äô one of three (12 in total once they‚Äôre all unlocked) special attacks, which range from Saaya‚Äôs crowd-controlling earthquake to Kagura‚Äôs ability to spawn a doppelganger that allows her to accrue double damage. This all goes without mentioning how each character can briefly transform into hyper-erotic Super Saiyans‚Ä¶

But before I get too carried away with how delightful the combat can be, I must address a few of Z2: Chaos‚Äô issues. Primarily, although the ladies‚Äô character models are lovely and detailed, and the enemies are oddly designed yet distinguishable, the stages are embarrassingly barren, poor representations of the real-world locations they‚Äôre barely trying to parallel. Dubai, for instance, looks less like a metropolis stacked with ultramodern architecture and more like a colossus‚Äô litter box, with its static sand dunes and ‚Äì what the hell is that, a miniature Mayan temple? On top of this, the stages suffer from length imbalances. One stage, or chapter, may take five minutes to complete, while a later chapter will take almost an hour. What this can do in a game that focuses on repeatedly punishing waves of enemies is add tedium to its formula by the end of the game‚Äôs 5 to 7 hour campaign. It‚Äôs not an issue for me, since I enjoy a good grind, but for some it could prove to feel more like labor than leisure by the time you reach the final stage.

Onechanbara Z2: Chaos has its issues. Although it has a nonsensical story (which I enjoy), level design from the deep yesteryears of virtual entertainment, and stages that vary so wildly in length that I forget the day of the week, Z2: Chaos‚Äô combat nearly renders all of these calamitous flaws silent. It‚Äôs not the deepest, most intelligent, or most skill-intensive combat on the market. But it might be the most eccentric. And with the right mindset that‚Äôs willing to embrace the zaniness and work around the possible weaknesses, it can be just as fun as the best hack ‚Äòn‚Äô slashes around.gned to square, triangle, and circle, respectively ‚Äì and when executing a weak combo sequence, which consists of tapping square in succession, you have the freedom to change up this basic combo by adding a few strong and sub weapon attacks into the mix. This all goes without mentioning how each character can briefly transform into hyper-erotic Super Saiyans‚Ä¶

Dubai, for instance, looks less like a metropolis stacked with ultramodern architecture and more like a colossus litter box, with its static sand dunes and ‚Äì what the hell is that, a miniature Mayan temple? Although it has a nonsensical story (which I enjoy), level design from the deep yesteryears of virtual entertainment, and stages that vary so wildly in length that I forget the day of the week, Z2: Chaos‚Äô combat nearly renders all of these calamitous flaws silent. It‚Äôs not the deepest, most intelligent, or most skill-intensive combat on the market. But it might be the most eccentric. And with the right mindset that‚Äôs willing to embrace the zaniness and work around the possible weaknesses, it can be just as fun as the best hack ‚Äòn‚Äô slashes around.

column6: TrackMania Turbo: Build to Race
column14:
The game shipped on time and was in new condition as stated. The box and instructions were all there.

Overall the game is awesome. The races are quick, fun, and have a good variety. In single player there's a ton of tracks to play through as well as the track builder option which could keep you busy almost indefinitely. You play through the single player to unlock more unique parts for building custom tracks. It's very fun in that the tracks are fun to play even if you have no interest in unlocking parts. Some tracks can be really challenging but not at all impossible if you stick to it. It's very fun playing with others in the multiplayer mode as well. Everyone uses cars that are equal so it is all a matter of skill. The games are very competitive and great for a group of friends. The "matches" are short so you could play in a short amount of time or just keep playing if you have lots of time.

The graphics are on par for other Wii games. The detail into the mechanics is above average for a Wii game and the controls are easy to master. There is no language or violence in this game and would be suitable for any age in that regard but from a difficulty stand point I would say that it would be best for ages over 12.

Overall it's probably my favorite racing game for Wii along with Mario Kart Wii

column6: Sennheiser U 320 Multi-Platform Gaming Headset
column14: There is very little to complain about with this headset. The sound is fantastic. The design is lovely. The comfort is phenomenal. But because there is something to complain about, I'll leave a more in-depth review.  First: buy a cord management system. If you're a PC gamer, you know why, but if you're a console gamer and sit closer than 15' from your tv, you'll need it too. The generous cord length is nothing to sniff at (it's probably very useful for anyone with a home theater) and if you have animals and small children, cord management is a necessity.  That being said, it's not a complaint. I bought a Dotz organizer as one reviewer recommended and it fits the bill exactly after some initial adjusting, I didn't have to worry about the surplus wiring.  DESIGN The u320 has a classic look to it that very much fits with a modern, sleeker (almost minimalist) theme. It's by no means bulky, and with a sleek black finish and smooth blue accent ring on each can, you can rest assured that you look as good as you'll game. (Personally, I showed mine off to my fellow gamers and hoped at least one of them would notice the quarter note design. None did.) If a product's looks weigh in on your decision to buy it, you'll love these.  COMFORT For some background: I'm used to EX-05s with metal bands, some padding, and some netting. And by "used to" I mean I wore them for a year until I couldn't stand it any more because of the headaches the headset gave me. When I looked for a new set, I immediately looked for comfort. I can handle crap sound quality as long as I can understand roughly what's going on. Imagine my joy when I found these: lightweight with larger cans gently padded. Still, I was skeptical - who knew what the pressure was going to be like.  It is virtually unnoticeable.  I put on the headset and was amazed. I couldn't (can't) feel any sort of pressure point of any kind, my cheeks and jaw don't hurt while wearing them, the headband is evenly distributed over my head... I wear glasses, and there seems to be a little gap specifically designed to keep the arms from pressing into your head while you game (which has been the cause of one too many headaches with my old headphones). The padding is nice and breathable, to prevent overheating ears, and there's plenty of ear space. I have large ears even for my larger head and don't feel the least bit bothered by the amount of space provided. You might fall asleep in these by forgetting you have them on in the first place.  DURABILITY But don't worry if you do, they won't fall apart on you. Despite the lightweight design, these headphones are built to last. The band is made of plastic that flexes easily but feels durable, should you feel like slamming your headphones to the floor in troll-induced rage. The foam padding isn't the type to crumble away, which is fantastic. Why some people call it composed out of cheap materials, I'll never know - you can twist the headbands a fair amount with no signs of stress and no hint of cracking. The ear cuffs feel pretty secure, given the wiggle room. The material doesn't feel cheap in least.  That being said: if you are one to abuse your headphones, you might not want to get a $170 pair in the first place. If you're not, go for it.  SOUND Full disclosure: I'm a musician as well as a gamer. Finding something that lets me appreciate the rumble of drums and sweet sounds of woodwind instruments is just as important to me as finding something that let's me hear footsteps and ambiance while playing.  I'm not saying your KDR will improve overnight. But with these headphones, you have the potential to adjust your settings to better suit your playstyle as well as enjoy the effort put into the score of the games you're playing. Killing a frost troll or slaughtering a horde of Fallen will feel that much more epic, and in Skyrim, dragons will cower before your Thu'um. This headset brings forth every bit of detail you could want, including things that normally get lost behind a roar or hail of gunfire.  It won't improve your KDR overnight. But it will let you hear things that may make that improvement possible.  And if you want to cheer with your friends over a raid, they'll hear you as clearly as you'll hear them. When you don't feel like listening to them, just adjust the chat volume and enjoy the game. When you don't feel like talking, just lid the boom mic. Speaking of which...  MIC You mute yourself my lifting the mic away from your mouth like you normally would. No, really, just lift the mic and they won't hear you. Lower it if you want them to hear.  There are controls that let you adjust the mic volume so you're not yelling in your friend's ear, a there is a talkback feature so you can hear how you sound to others. Both work as intended.  The noise cancellation is nice, though I play in a quiet environment and couldn't really test it out. My brother heard me clearly (he was playing upstairs) and other than the dogs barking directly into the mic noticed very little other noise. No static or muffling to note.  OVERALL Head shape will influence this, but these were amazingly comfortable to me. The sound coming out of the speakers was lovely and crisp, with every detail pronounced. I'm not even mad that these aren't Dolby Digital 7.1 or 5.1; I love them!  That being said, I'm kind of bummed they don't come with an audio adapter for the 360. If you're going to listen to the best, you're going to want to watch the best you can, right? So an HDMI cable is a necessity. It's a little thing, granted, but a thing it is. (I bought a $6 Trenro 360 RCA Audio and Digital Cable Adapter for myself and my brother, but other people may want to go more name-brand-y. Turtle Beach sells audio adapters for something like $15 an adapter.)  All in all, this is a fantastic product I would recommend to anyone who wants their auditory experience to be top of the line.  The two-year warranty should something happen isn't bad either.r.

column6: Diablo III - PC/Mac
column13: Worth the Price now, especially for Adventure Mode.
column14:
The current price decrease from $39.99 to now $25 (not sure how long it will be there), for Reaper of Souls is now worth it. TONS of changes occurred to Diablo III right before this expansion launched and boy, was it needed. A warn of caution when purchasing this through Amazon or other retail outlets: buy it digitally. Like World of Warcraft expansions, owning physical standard edition of games and expansions from Blizzard are literally pointless now. Since you HAVE to be online to play Diablo III anyway, you are just buying the Reaper of Souls expansion code to upgrade your Diablo III license on Battle.net. But onto what you get:
Ideally, there are 3 features added to RoS:

1 new Class, the Crusader. It's an interesting class that's perfect for Diablo III and very reminiscent of the Paladin from DII. It has some very stylized abilities like the steed charge and stacking/passive buffs on their shields. But ultimately, nothing special compared to the Druid from DII LoD. Most players may play it once or twice then go back to the characters they put more effort into.

1 new Act (ActV). This is the part that people had issues with and basing the entirety of the expansion on. Ideally you can beat this act roughly in 2-3 hours on normal difficulty. It was 9 hours for me to complete the act because I was actually exploring and doing as much as I can before the end and was on Expert and above difficulty because I wanted a challenge...Like you are supposed to. The story is nothing special as usual. In fact you don't really see the Malthiel (the boss on the cover) till literally the very end. New locations like Westmarch are impressive to look at and have more nooks and crannies to explore, even random dungeon instances which was needed terribly in DIII's acts.

Adventure Mode. It is literally awesome not having to do the same acts and pressing the space bar to skip through the story dialogue over and over and over again. After completing Act V the first time, you can select this mode for any of your characters; new and old, Hardcore or Seasonal. You can pick any Act area of DIII and RoS and perform bounties or Rifts at whatever difficulty level you feel comfortable at.

Overall, Reaper of Souls is a continuing effort from Blizzard to make amends with the backlash Diablo III received. As I finish this review, Blizzard has already added almost a year's worth of patches and new content. As of now, DIII is worth playing, but you'll have to make sure you install this. Adventure mode was sorely needed, but it's unfortunate that you have to buy RoS to utilize this. DIII could have used this back then to create longevity in the post launch Inferno days.this mode for any of your characters; new and old, Hardcore or Seasonal. You can pick any Act area of DIII and RoS and perform bounties or Rifts at whatever difficulty level you feel comfortable at. Overall, Reaper of Souls is a continuing effort from Blizzard to make amends with the backlash Diablo III received. As I finish this review, Blizzard has already added almost a year's worth of patches and new content. As of now, DIII is worth playing, but you'll have to make sure you install this. Adventure mode was sorely needed, but it's unfortunate that you have to buy RoS to utilize this. DIII could have used this back then to create longevity in the post launch Inferno days.

column6: Sony Borderlands 2 - Limited Edition - PlayStation Vita Bundle
column13: The original PS Vita is a fantastic handheld system that is drastically underrated
column14:
The original PS Vita is a fantastic handheld system that is drastically underrated. It has a plethora of great games and a great looking 5-in OLED touch-screen that makes the colors look vibrant. The PS Vita is also the first ever handheld gaming system to have two analog sticks and a back touch-pad. There was some problems though. The system is pretty powerful, it touts a quad-core CPU, 512MB of RAM, and 128MB of VRAM. With that power, the battery life had to be affected. On a single gaming session it lasted about 3-5 hours. Also the back-touchpad was a little big, there was some accidental presses here and there; and the original PS Vita was a little heavy, causing some strain during long gaming sessions.

The long awaited slim redesign of the PlayStation Vita has finally come out overseas. The PS Vita Slim lives up to it's name, it is about 20% thinner and 15% lighter. The weight and height differences are totally noticeable and as a result the slim model is much more comfortable to hold for a extended gameplay session. The system itself looks fantastic. It looks modern, with its rounded corners; and the build quality is great, it does not feel like a cheap knock off of its older brother.

The PS Vita game slot is easier to access and has been moved to the middle at the top. The original had it on the top but to the right and to the left of it was a mystery port that was never used which is now absent in the newest model. Gone is also the proprietary charging cable which is now a standard micro-usb charger that you get with almost every handheld device that is not made by Apple.

The battery life in the slim model is better than the original. The battery lasts a little more than a hour longer and pumped out gamings that were about 4-6 hours long on a single charge. The better battery life does come at a cost though. Instead of the originals beautiful OLED screen, the slim has a LCD screen. Yes, the LCD is not as vibrant as the OLED. The LCD still makes everything happening on the PS Vita look great. You can only tell a difference if you put the 2 models side by side. Honestly, I would rather have the longer battery life with a minor downgrade in screen quality anyday.

The software portion of the system is exactly the same across both of the models. The LiveArea is still as quick and snappy as ever. You can play games, earn PSN trophies, download a plethora of games off the PlayStation Store via WiFi or usb transfer, surf the web with decent web browser, setup calendar events, read emails, look at maps, listen to music, watch movies, and view pictures or take them with the same poor quality 3MP cameras that are only good for skype.

You can organize your games into folders. Each game has a LiveArea the the developers can fully customize with links to websites, news updates, leaderboards, and much more. Your friends can give a like or comment on in-game activities that you have accomplished within the LiveArea also.

The PS Vita can also remotely connect with PS3 games and play a few of them or connect with the PS4 and play almost every game available for the PS4. Remote-Play works fantastically on the PS Vita and it works great as a second controller for the PS4.

The buttons and speakers almost remain the same between the two. The buttons are in good locations and have a nice responsiveness to them. The Home, Start, and Select buttons are much better now. Instead of hard to press little ovals, they are now nicely sized circles that are now much easier to press. The back-touchpad has also received an upgrade. The touchpad is smaller which mean no more accidental presses. The speakers are still crisp and clear although they still lack in the bass department.

As awesome as the PS Vita is there is still one glaring problem that both the models have, memory card prices. The slim model does have 1GB of built-in memory but it becomes useless becauseyou can not use it in a combination with a memory card. It's either the 1GB or the memory card, not both. Thankfully the slim model out now comes with a 8GB memory card and Borderlands 2, which is a great game. If you ever want to upgrade your storage just be prepared to pay a pretty penny to be able to afford the 16GB and the 32GB memory card.

The PS Vita Slim is still a great handheld that has plenty of great games to play around with. Everything that Sony has changed is for the better with the slim model. It is lighter, thinner, and overall more comfortable to hold for a long period of time. It is still an attractive looking system with great looking screen, although not as good as the originals OLED. The battery life lasts a little more than an hour longer as far as gaming goes than on the original. The only huge downfall is the memory card prices which will make the system $50-$100 more expensive if you want to upgrade your storage. As of the time of this review, the PS Vita Slim comes bundled with Borderlands 2 and a 8GB memory card for $199.99 which is a fine price for what you getyou can not use it in a combination with a memory card. It's either the 1GB or the memory card, not both. Thankfully the slim model out now comes with a 8GB memory card and Borderlands 2, which is a great game. If you ever want to upgrade your storage just be prepared to pay a pretty penny to be able to afford the 16GB and the 32GB memory card.

The PS Vita Slim is still a great handheld that has plenty of great games to play around with. Everything that Sony has changed is for the better with the slim model. It is lighter, thinner, and overall more comfortable to hold for a long period of time. It is still an attractive looking system with great looking screen, although not as good as the originals OLED. The battery life lasts a little more than an hour longer as far as gaming goes than on the original. The only huge downfall is the memory card prices which will make the system $50-$100 more expensive if you want to upgrade your storage. As of the time of this review, the PS Vita Slim comes bundled with Borderlands 2 and a 8GB memory card for $199.99 which is a fine price for what you get

column6: Mpow® Dragon Slayer Wireless Optical Gaming Game Mouse Mice Adjustable DPI Function:1000-1600-2400-4000 for PC/Computer
column14:
Its a pretty good budget gaming mouse! The feel, comfort, and responsiveness are above what I would expect for the money (I paid 15$ for this on sale). I would recommend this mouse for MOBA games, casual gaming, or any other game that does not require a million buttons or faster-than-humanly-possible response time. Competitive FPS players may want to look elsewhere, but honestly your network will have much more of an effect on your K/D than any mouse ever could.

I game on a mac and windows, and surprisingly the features on the extra buttons worked well on OSX, which is more than I could say for my razer bluetooth mouse.

Also note, this mouse is probably best for the "palm-grip" type user, since the molding on the sides makes it somewhat non-ergonomic to hold with your thumb and ring/pinky fingers. I am a "claw-grab" type of mouser, so I ended up giving it to my little cousin who loves it.

The only complaint I have is that the lighting only has a alternating mode that constantly dims on and off while switching colors, kinda like Christmas lights. I prefer to turn the lights off and save battery so it is a non-issue for me personally, but for those looking to color-coordinate their setup should take note.

column6: Metal Gear Rising Revengeance
column13: Lemme Cut Right to It: Revengeance Rules
column14:
Konami may have kept us waiting, but, man, did they deliver. A sharp left turn from Metal Gears of old, Revengeance proves a tireless assault on the senses as developer PlatinumGames eviscerated the deliberate and lengthy stealth-play of earlier entries in favor of a full-on barrage of ultra-violent insanity.

Metal Gear enthusiasts, rest easy: while MGRR's clear focus on lightning-paced, precision melee encounters eschews the series' foundations of tactical restraint, none its predecessors' tension or challenge is lost here. Gameplay is tight, unforgiving, and completely rewarding: while levels are fairly linear, combat is always varied. Take to the streets of a war-torn city and cut a swath of destruction through that army of mercs in front of you, or run up the side of a building (!!!) and rain death from above with a devastating lunge right into the unsuspecting crowd. Close-quarter sword fights are about as good as they come, featuring an endlessly exhilarating countering system and (the crown-jewel) a slow-mo free slicing mode which lets you cut your enemies to ribbons and use their battery-powered guts to recharge your cybernetic ninja powers. The boss battles are phenomenal, chalk-full of spectacular set-pieces and elaborate, multi-tiered challenges.

Those hoping for anything more than Metal Gear fan-service out of the story in Revengeance will be disappointed. Picking up a few years after MGS4, an infinitely less whiny and brooding Raiden goes on a bloody quest for (lo-and-behold) revenge after a generic president of a made-up African country he's protecting gets assassinated under his watch. Cue a typical Metal Gear-esque convoluted conspiracy yarn about the world's need for a "War Economy", introductions to ensemble of paper-thin and stereotypical supporting voices in Raiden's ear, ham-tastic villains, and Kojima humor galore. At a brisk four or five hours, Revengeance never outstays its welcome, though: the cut-scenes are shorter than any of the series prior entries, and the story is just as consciously ridiculous as the action. Sure there's plenty of BS in the narrative, but Revengeance is all about cutting through the BS with a razor-sharp katana, and super-charging itself on its battery-powered guts.

These days, MGRR is a steal. New Game+ features are abundant, as are the ever-present Metal Gear VR missions. Free DLC packs for two supporting characters are fun, as well, and add another three or four hours of carnage to the already impressive package. It's a terrific game: Ninja Run to the internet and pick this one up!

column6: LEGO The Hobbit
column13: Shockingly, it completely omits HOBBIT film three (battle of the 5 Armies) but you get a playable Tom Bombidil
column14: I love the LEGO GAMES and LOTR, I love the LOTR LEGO toys even, but The Lord of the Rings Lego games are the weakest of their consistently successful franchise. One flaw with both with are the open world map that mixes side quests with main story. It can become very difficult to find where your main story thread had left off if you stop playing before you've solved the main story. Speaking of the main story for the first time in any LEGO game I've run across the main story is shockingly incomplete, there is no Battle of the Five Armies third film content not if there any true resolution to poor Bilbo Bagins Quest! After defeating The Dragon in a manner that will make fans of LOTR literature or films baffled and appalled at the limits of LEGO retcons, the credits roll! I was shocked. Given the nature of X Box downloadable content and the move to turn a one time purchase into a series of future buys, I expected there to be a Hobbit 3 expansion game in the future. Like most LEGO GAMES certain characters can do certain things you need to advance the game and solve puzzles (sadly 70% look nearly identical), if you try to use an equal character in freeplay you most likely find that you can't finish a boss fight if you forget who was in the original story mode. You also have difficulty getting side quest character to realize and reward you for finishing said side quests. This game is particularly choosy about how you may used ranged weapons and inconsistent distinctions between sling and bow, you have very little freedom even in freeplay (but then it's nearly impossible to keep unlocked weapons without digging through inventory each time you swap). One new element to the game is clearly inspired by Minecraft, you need to collect, not only money studs, but raw materials for making things (many of the side quest are getting plans and supplies to do just that). So you'll spend twices much time picking things up.  But hats off for LEGO designers for including TOM BOMBADIL who missed all 6 film adaptions (even Radagast made a few), granted his special power is digging and growing but, mah.missed all 6 film adaptions (even Radagast made a few), granted his special power is digging and growing but, mah.

column6: One Piece: Pirate Warriors / Kaizoku Musou PS3 Game (English language) for PlayStation 3
column13: A great starting point for the series
column14:
If one thing can be said for certain, it is that Omega Force knows how to make a game. On the off chance that the name doesn‚Äôt ring a bell, they are the developers for Temco Koei‚Äôs Warrior series. Dynasty, Samurai, Orochi, we are all pretty big fans of and that doesn‚Äôt include Hyrule Warriors, Bladestorm, Toukiden, the upcoming Dragon Quest Heroes.

So with all that being said, I don‚Äôt know how One Piece Pirate Warriors avoided me for so long. My initial response at the announcement of One Piece Pirate Warriors 3 was honestly ‚ÄúThere are two others?‚Äù. Within not very long I set out to find the first two and thankfully they were happily placed upon the PSN where I promptly jumped into them as they were infinitely easier to find than physical copies which in some cases were as much as a mortgage for some reason. Being just slightly behind in the Manga as I like to read arcs as a whole without the weekly cliffhangers, returning over seven-hundred chapters back to the beginning was a nice refresher.

The great thing about a Warriors game is that there is always something new whether it be big or small. One Piece Pirate Warriors is no exception with Luffy and his Crew put into somewhat of a Musou style. Instead of going about a full blown warriors game with over a thousand KOs per map, things were interestingly different both in good and frustrating ways depending upon the situation.

Going about a different direction than a lot of the core Warriors series entries, One Piece instead uses the main character‚Äôs abilities for a lot of action, adventure, and light puzzle solving. For those that do not really know what One Piece is, it is a weekly Shonen Jump entry alongside the likes of Bleach (Death Gods), Fairy Tail (Wizards), and the recently finished Naruto (Ninjas). It‚Äôs about a bunch of crazy pirates in which some have eaten fruits that grant them powers at the cost of not being able to swim. The main character Luffy D. Monkey is in this boat as he‚Äôs eaten the Gum-Gum Fruit essentially turning his entire body to Rubber. Using this idea as a core, Pirate Warriors is essentially split into two different portions. The first is a good old Musou style conquering areas and defeating bosses while the other is an action-adventure-puzzle that uses Luffy‚Äôs rubberized body to get through it all.

When it comes to the straight up Warriors sections, Pirate Warriors does everything right. If I had to put an approximation I would say that about ninety-percent of the time players will be using Luffy with some quick segments with other characters especially later on in the game. Combat itself is fluid with a bit of Samurai Warriors mixed in for combos being based off of both the Square and the Triangle button instead of just using one or the other for a finishing move like a lot of the other entries. This definitely allowed for a lot more versatility especially since you had only the one character for the majority of the game.

Supplementing not being able to change your main character is the option to partner up with other members of your crew when they are available. By doing so, Partner Strikes open up allowing for them to switch places with Luffy for the duration of a combo attack. To set up a partner strike, a specific combo is listed beneath Luffy‚Äôs health bar. By performing this combo and then hitting L2 when the option arises in slow motion on your screen, you instantly change places for some rather large scale enemy destruction depending upon the partner. On a general basis though, any Partner Strike is a good Partner Strike. By repeatedly using these as they become available, a meter filled up on the partner‚Äôs portrait. Once filled, the next Partner Strike will also unleash a Musou attack for maximum efficiency.

Here‚Äôs where things get a bit better and worse. The inclusion of a different style of levels was a great idea. Using Luffy‚Äôs rubber body, players can extend their limbs to slingshot themselves over larger distances, reach high ledges in order to make it up and over obstacles, extend over a gap in order to pull down bridges, etc. On these stages the fighting is much less as the platforming and the puzzle challenges are really what are being highlighted. What can kind of get in the way however is that sometimes it could take a few seconds and backtracking could be required. While this is generally the norm of things, some platforming elements are just too much to be repeated that often in that short amount of time especially if you miss your cue and fall down having to restart. The main example of this would be the monkey bars. Using a full combination of L1, L2, R1, R2 Luffy needs to hit the appropriate ones in sequence to make it over. There‚Äôs one level in particular that after six times I had more than enough and just wanted to get to the boss fight.

That leads into the other half issue. Boss fights could be both amazing and amazingly frustrating. The frustrating boss fights are those that have no mechanics to them but instead are a full out brawl. These generally have Luffy up against foes that should technically be able to pull off a one hit kill with how strong Luffy is at that point in time. These battles can be very long even after learning the attack patterns as one wrong move can send you to the game over screen.

Boss battles with mechanics attached to them however are much more pleasant and generally fun to play. These battles contain options to throw things at the boss in order to get in a coup de gras or a bit of platforming elements to dodge devastating attacks. If anything can be said though, it is that there is a lot outside the norm when it comes to Pirate Warriors which boils down to being pretty standard for the general craziness of One Piece.

Not being left out there was one more feature that was included amongst everything else which can mostly be seen between the Boss fights and certain Platforming segments. Quick Time Events (QTEs) are used mainly in boss fights to show off some cinematic fight scenes to spice things up in an epic anime showdown fashion that One Piece and a lot of Shonen Jump (Dragon Ball Kamehamehas included) are really known for. In platforming they are used much less until the slingshots or the monkey bars are put into focus. I these players have to as mentioned above hit the right combinations or risk falling down which is generally into water. Since our powered up Pirate can‚Äôt swim, we really don‚Äôt want that.

One Piece Pirate Warriors came out a few years ago back in 2012 with it‚Äôs sequel Pirate Warriors 2 in 2013. While it may be slightly older, it doesn‚Äôt quite yet fit into the retro section so I will be giving it a score. Honestly even with the bits of bumps that it has, Pirate Warriors is a good game which shows off a decent amount of innovation attempted by the team in order to do something wacky like One Piece justice. I‚Äôll be back soon with Pirate Warriors 2 as I get ready for next months Pirate Warriors 3!yers can extend their limbs to slingshot themselves over larger distances, reach high ledges in order to make it up and over obstacles, extend over a gap in order to pull down bridges, etc. On these stages the fighting is much less as the platforming and the puzzle challenges are really what are being highlighted. What can kind of get in the way however is that sometimes it could take a few seconds and backtracking could be required. While this is generally the norm of things, some platforming elements are just too much to be repeated that often in that short amount of time especially if you miss your cue and fall down having to restart. The main example of this would be the monkey bars. Using a full combination of L1, L2, R1, R2 Luffy needs to hit the appropriate ones in sequence to make it over. There‚Äôs one level in particular that after six times I had more than enough and just wanted to get to the boss fight.

That leads into the other half issue. Boss fights could be both amazing and amazingly frustrating. The frustrating boss fights are those that have no mechanics to them but instead are a full out brawl. These generally have Luffy up against foes that should technically be able to pull off a one hit kill with how strong Luffy is at that point in time. These battles can be very long even after learning the attack patterns as one wrong move can send you to the game over screen.

Boss battles with mechanics attached to them however are much more pleasant and generally fun to play. These battles contain options to throw things at the boss in order to get in a coup de gras or a bit of platforming elements to dodge devastating attacks. If anything can be said though, it is that there is a lot outside the norm when it comes to Pirate Warriors which boils down to being pretty standard for the general craziness of One Piece.

Not being left out there was one more feature that was included amongst everything else which can mostly be seen between the Boss fights and certain Platforming segments. Quick Time Events (QTEs) are used mainly in boss fights to show off some cinematic fight scenes to spice things up in an epic anime showdown fashion that One Piece and a lot of Shonen Jump (Dragon Ball Kamehamehas included) are really known for. In platforming they are used much less until the slingshots or the monkey bars are put into focus. I these players have to as mentioned above hit the right combinations or risk falling down which is generally into water. Since our powered up Pirate can‚Äôt swim, we really don‚Äôt want that.

One Piece Pirate Warriors came out a few years ago back in 2012 with it‚Äôs sequel Pirate Warriors 2 in 2013. While it may be slightly older, it doesn‚Äôt quite yet fit into the retro section so I will be giving it a score. Honestly even with the bits of bumps that it has, Pirate Warriors is a good game which shows off a decent amount of innovation attempted by the team in order to do something wacky like One Piece justice. I‚Äôll be back soon with Pirate Warriors 2 as I get ready for next months Pirate Warriors 3!

column14: I'm not sure how this product received so many good reviews. Maybe people just like the nostalgia of it? Maybe people don't remember how great the original NES controller is compared to this. Maybe people have never used an original NES controller so don't know any better.  I honestly have no idea but as soon as I started using this I knew something was off. I remember using a NES controller from 15+ years ago. I still distinctly remember the weight of the controller, the feel of it, and how to use it.  Right off the bat I could tell this thing was lighter but that's forgivable, I'm sure with more modern technology they were able to do away with a lot of unnecessary (by today's standards) components. The feel of the controller isn't quite the same but again that's also forgivable, I'm sure it's difficult to get something 100% right.  What is unforgivable is the horrible D pad. Yes, horrible. At first I thought it was something I was doing wrong, like maybe I forgot how to properly use a NES controller. I remember being able to flawlessly transition from pushing right to pushing up without ever removing my thumb from the D pad and it would work perfectly; my character would go from moving right to up without a hitch.  With this controller though it's a total crapshoot, it might work perfectly or your character might just keep moving right even though you are now pushing up.  I read a review from another person that summed up this problem perfectly. The problem is if you push down on the center of the D pad the entire D pad moves down, as if you are pushing all 4 directions at once, and that's the problem, you don't want the whole D pad moving down at once.  I pulled out my original NES controller and sure enough, just as I remembered, it was impossible to have the whole D pad move down at the same time if you push the middle of it. The D pad is bound to be leaning towards one direction if you push down the center, meaning only one direction is pushed at once.  I bought a NES controller/USB converter so I could plug my original NES controller into my computer and it is exactly how I remember playing my original NES. The D pad works flawlessly. The buttons work flawlessly. It is perfect.  If you can put up with a poor functioning D pad then this product is alright, it's a bit cheaper than the converter plug alone so it has that going for it.  However if you actually want to enjoy your games I highly recommend buying the converter plug. If you don't already have a NES controller I would recommend paying the extra money to get one and the converter plug. This product is just absolutely aggravating to use.
