column6: Way of the Samurai 4 (Playstation 3) [UK IMPORT]
column13: Not what you might expect - but in a good way
column14:
I have played some interesting games up to this point in my life and Way of the Samurai 4 is absolutely one title that can fall into that category. You begin by getting off of a small boat in the tiny port town of Amihama during mid 19th Century Japan. What do you from this point on is entirely and literally up to you.

I have to preface this by saying that there is just about nothing serious in the tone of Way of the Samurai 4, other than the time period and the changes that Japan was going through. Never taking itself seriously, there is a lot of fun to be had - especially if you don‚Äôt mind the crazy characters and townspeople that you can run into while strolling about the town in nothing more than boxer shorts. Yes you read that right. I forwent the Kimono and traditional Japanese underwear for a pair of blue and white striped modern day boxers. I eventually found a long pipe to go with that as I strode around bare foot, surprisingly never being looked at twice. Guess I wasn‚Äôt the weirdest person there with all the British wearing their dresses, three piece suits, and top hats.

Before being left entirely to your own devices, there is a prologue that offers to teach players the basics in the form of being told what to do by a common townswoman. Then again, considering that she teaches you both basic and advanced moves by yelling at you as to how to do them‚Ä¶ I seriously wouldn‚Äôt want to meet her in a dark alley as she knows what she‚Äôs doing. While the basics may be simple with light and heavy attacks, dodging and blocking, putting them into play will be an entirely different story and will take time to get right.

While a lot of the dialog, character personalities, and random townsfolk fall into the weird, fun and quirky categories, combat takes itself very seriously. There is no goofing around for this samurai and his weapons. If you fight and your enemy and lose, you‚Äôre Dead.

Game Over Man, Game Over.

This took me a bit by surprise the first time that it happened as I had barely gotten my feet wet so to speak. I accidentally chose dialog in the opening fight making myself surrender as I tried to quickly yell a taunt, was then tied up and thrown onto train tracks, saved but lost everything that I carried, and then picked a fight with a side quest mark after having told a woman being stalked that I would up put a stop to it. I faced the stalker while being barehanded and lost. Miserably...

Once faced with the dreaded game over screen I realized one of two things. A) I had to get better and not suck so much the next time and B) Way of the Samurai 4 almost has a Roguelike element to it as any experience in martial art styles and weapon forms are kept and carried forward along with a few other little things on your next attempt at life. Starting right back on that boat leading up to the docks, players can once again decide to follow the same first decisions or go about another route.

Once back and into the tutorial fray I actually decided not to sully my blade but instead use my fists of awesomeness and toss my enemies around like ragdolls until they couldn‚Äôt move anymore which is another of the charms that showed itself. Swords aren‚Äôt everything and different weapon styles or lack there of are just as fun as one another.

Way of the Samurai 4 in a lot of ways made me think of Akiba‚Äôs Trip in the way that you have access to an entire town at all times to do really whatever you want to do. Once you are taught the basics, the town is at your fingertips. At this point I honestly stood there taking everything in and wondering to myself‚Ä¶ what do I do now? I‚Äôll be honest that open-ended / open-world games are generally not my thing as I much prefer to play something with an actual direction that provides distractions but also a clear course. So what is one to do? I went after thugs for a good while better my armed and unarmed combat skills while picking up money and other weapons to disassemble or sell.

One thing that didn‚Äôt take long to notice was that if I‚Äôm really going to last against tougher foes then I was going to need a better weapon. Enter the very well oiled and muscular man that happens to be the Blacksmith. Here is a man that can make modifications to your weapon by upgrading the base strength to making it harder. Like everything that I‚Äôve been through of late there is a catch to performing such a feat and that is that by upgrading the strength of the weapon, you decrease its durability. Honestly, this felt more than a fair trade as I didn‚Äôt have to swing or block as much to even kill some certified badasses that what into town after a few events. Being on par with them was more than worth it.

Fighting in the streets was generally not an issue depending upon the part of town that you could currently find yourself in. Fighting in the wrong part of town however, the upper quarters, it didn‚Äôt take long to get yourself arrested. This is another part that just felt like it was off the wall and made me wonder where they got their ideas. So getting arrested I figured wasn‚Äôt so bad until I found myself tied up, again as it wasn't the first time, and then suspended upon a spiked wooden horse.

The wooden horse itself is not a very pleasant torture device, being a torture device and all, but adding spikes on it was just cruel. This became a mini-game of sorts as you had to balance yourself under the torturer‚Äôs whip but also stay above the horse. Eventually flames were turned on, she would lash out with a kick and then I figured ‚Äúalright‚Äù I‚Äôll pass out when my health drops to zero. Oh no. I died. Again. What is this Dark Souls? Alright, back to the boat! Time to start again...

For all the interesting systems that Way of the Samurai 4 has in place it also has a few smaller issues. One of the ones that actually annoyed me a bit more than I thought it would was that the voices and the movement of the mouths never really seemed to match up. Now if this was a case of an original Japanese game and English voices then that is something that most of us are so used to that we think nothing of it. In this case however we have a Japanese game with Japanese voices and it was honestly rather distracting as that just about never happens.

While exploring the town it could feel at times that things weren‚Äôt exactly where they were ‚Äúmeant‚Äù to be. Running around I would be hitting into other people and making them mad for ‚Äúnot watching where I was going‚Äù even if it looked like there was more than enough space between us. The same would happen when taking just a single step too far when trying to simply talk and they would be bouncing back as if I was a 500 pound sumo wrestler that was on his way to breakfast and they were between me and food. Once or twice was fine, but having to almost use a snail's pace to talk to someone could get a bit annoying and drop the pace while running around trying to take care of a few things before the time of day moved on possibly making you miss you opportunity to perform a side quest until the next day.

Way of the Samurai 4 is a crazy entry that doesn‚Äôt take itself serious based while still keeping itself based on a particular era of Japanese history after the British came to call. If you want to be a the good guy, the bad guy, or the whatever guy, all of that is up to with however you feel at that moment in time. The replay value is huge, with a lot of events that can only be seen if you manage to live long enough to see the results of your decisions. In certain cases‚Ä¶ that won‚Äôt be long.ombat skills while picking up money and other weapons to disassemble or sell.

column6: Phineas and Ferb Ride Again - Nintendo DS
column14:
They essentially took the first one and threw in some platformers. The reason why I really liked the first one was because it didn't take much coordination to play, but when this one got to the first Perry vs. Doof battle, this game became just like a classic platform game, and it was so hard that I had to hand it to my game-savvy brother to beat, and even he found it difficult. I was sort of thinking, "Okay, but I can enjoy the levels between Perry battles, right?" A few minutes later, they threw in another platformer, and I wound up frustrated all over again. It was about then that I put it down.

They did improve one thing from the original, though-- they changed the way the "busted meter" works, so that Candace gets mad when you could potentially get hurt, and not when you walk around. She does scream "PHINEAS!" which gets very annoying.

In short, if you liked the first one and you're good at platform games, you'll probably like this, but I didn't. Seriously disappointed.

column6: Railroad Tycoon 2 Platinum Edition - PC
column13: Great Game & A Basic Industrial Model to Study
column14:
In addition to building and running railroads you also have to run the business. Cargoes can have greater or smaller values dependent on the demand. And cargoes can create continuing cycles. An example is you have farms that grow wheat. You can haul the wheat to a bakery. Now the bakery produces food(bread), that can be hauled to cities and consumed. Or the wheat can be hauled to a cattle yard which will "grow" cattle and then you can haul the cattle to a meat packing plant. And the meat plant produces food to haul to cities. As you grow cities you get more people and mail you can haul between cities.
There are about a dozen paths cargoes can take thru various industries.

The car designs are fantastic, and it definitely captures the feel of good old action packed Saturday mornings. The story is predictable, but easily forgivable, as sometimes new material can be hard to come up with for a kids game.

column6: Nyko Data Bank
column14:
*** UPDATE April 2016 *** Playstation OS 3.50 fixed the 2TB drive size limit issue in Rest Mode. Rest Mode now works with drives larger than 2TB!!

Very fast, plug and play and works perfectly with [[ASIN:B00FQH7MQ2 Seagate 4TB SSHD SATA 6Gb/s 64MB Cache 3.5-Inch Internal Bare Drive (ST4000DX001)]] with one caveat; \\\Rest Mode\\\\\" does not work with this 4TB SSHD. (See update above - Rest Mode now works!)

I tried the Nyko with a 2TB drive and everything worked perfectly, including Rest Mode. It's the 4TB size that the Playstation 4 does not like in Rest Mode. I just shut down the PS4 completely and problem solved.

***IMPORTANT - You need the 800Mb PS4 update file - NOT the 250mb file, otherwise it will not reinstall the operating system and fail. [...] - Click on \\\\\"DOWNLOAD NOW\\\\\" to get complete 800mb file.

Other than that, it is an Excellent product, very highly recommended!

Clarification : If you use Rest Mode with this 4TB drive, your Playstation 4 will not wake properly; it will wake in Safe Mode and go through a disk check routine every time with sector errors. Just shut down your PS4 completely and problem solved.

This is not the fault of a 4TB drive - any drive above 2TB will do this. It is a Playstation 4 limitation. Perhaps a future PS4 firmware update will fix this problem, but for now, 2TB is the limit to Rest Mode. (See update above - Rest Mode now works!)"

column6: The Evil Within
column13: \You Look as Though You've Seen a Ghost\": A Flawed, Striking Journey Down the Good Ol' Rabbit Hole"
column14:
An atmospheric, pulpy love-letter to the genre he helped establish, Shinji Mikami's The Evil Within pays its homages in full, even if it struggles at times to get its own story straight.

Detective Sebastian Castellanos and company are thrust into an unfolding and utterly disorienting nightmare after getting called in to investigate a mysterious incident at a local asylum. Soon enough, the white-washed walls of the nuthouse are repainted red with blood, a hoodie-wearing albino specter is killing everyone in droves, and Sebastian is getting chased around by deranged denizens of an eerily familiar remote countryside village. We've been here before, but, then again, that's the point: the Evil Within isn't trying to break new ground so much as it tries to renovate the old mansion. Combat is challenging, enemies are fast, puzzles and traps are abundant, and boss encounters ooze dread in a way that more than makes up for latter Resident Evil entries' failings: this is root-level survival horror evolved.

While the Evil Within's grainy, grind-house visual palette and terrifically detailed environments are immersive and appropriately unsettling, its abrupt and often confounding story-line gets muddled quite early on. Even after the predictable twist is finally spelled-out in full, the game doesn't quite manage to pull the pieces together as well as it should. Characters, unsurprisingly, aren't particularly interesting or well-defined outside collectable journal entries, and our villain's motivations are ultimately a letdown.

That said, the game manages to push past its flaws in interesting ways, like engrossing mid-level location transitions and terrifying enemy design work. While adversaries all feature fantastic animations, it is a bit off-putting getting around as Sebastian early on in the game: between his flailing melee attacks and noodle-armed limping, Sebastian provides just as many laughs as his ghoulish pursuers elicit scares. Equallyhilarious is the atrocious dialogue on display: when a vicious, half-naked, spider-legged woman bursts out of a pool of blood on the ground a few hours into the game, Sebastian asks "What's with you lady?" completely unfazed. The voice-acting ranges between lazy (Anson Mount's Sebastian), sleepy (movie star Barry Pepper as Ruvik), and underutilized (Dexter-alum Jennifer Carpenter as Sebastian's new partner, Juli). Luckily, the sound-design more than makes up for the misfires in the casting department, offering a rich audio backdrop to the unfurling terrors at hand.

Along with a now perfunctory New Game+ mode, three enormously fun and equally atmospheric DLC expansions do a nice job building on the lackluster lore the main game's plot initially scuttled. "The Assignment", in particular, caters to the game's strengths, and does a great job dropping the spotlight on Sebastian's female partner, Juli. The main game itself spans a good 14 chapters, each an hour or less in length: the levels themselves are well varied and rarely redundant. Resident Evil and Silent Hill fans will find a lot to love here.

column6: KELUX Thumb Grips 10 Pack for PS4 Controllers (PlayStation 4)
column13: Don't waste money on over priced name brands, give these a try!
column14: I'm not reviewing how much this helps or hinders gameplay, while it undoubtedly is more comfortable than the bare thumbstick I find the benefits to precision to be negligible but other people swear by them. I'm going to assume you have already decided to buy grip covers/extenders and therefore will only be speaking to the quality of the product itself and why I find this exact item superior to similar products. You likely have seen the products made by KontrolFreak selling for about $15 a pair. The grip here are just as good at what they sell and for a fraction of the price. Additionally since the set comes with five different styles in three different heights you can experiment to find what you feel most comfortable with. The grips stay on without any adhesive and have a nice rubber feel that adds grip without feeling sticky. They don't interfere with normal control function. I personally like the concave  design with the dots around the edge and four triangles in the center. Not all brands are made equally. Beware of the 'silicone' grips being sold in a number of colors (often in a pack of 10 to 20) which can be identified by the eight bumps on top of the grip. These frequently fall off and because they are silicone they can be a bit slippery. Finally to save on production costs these don't come in any fancy packaging, instead you will receive them in a resealable clear plastic pouch.  [Update: The grip face does apparently wear out over time not unlike the tread of a tire. I currently have subjected my chosen favorite pair of grips to an estimated 1500+ hours of use but the wear is definitely noticeable , especially on the left thumb which is used more. They are still useful in their current condition and this hasn't  changed my opinion or rating But it should be mentioned they may eventually need to be replaced if your going to use them heavily. This may or may not be a issue with products from other companies (none of which make the exact design I've grown fondof)]  PROS - Comfort - Value - Large variety of styles included - Designed to not accidentally fall off  CONS - Would have liked to see a 6th control grip that was in the shortest size with a concave top. - Largest size has questionable practicality - Durability after extensive use (well over 1000 hours)  Pack includes 5 different designs - Short with studded grip top (basically height of original stick) - 2 Medium height, both slightly concaved with a center pattern and either a ringed or studded edge (personal favorite) - 2 Large height with concave top or studded grip top  Overall highly recommended for the casual or hardcore gamer, as well as everyone inbetween!
